00:00:38.430 --> 00:00:41.880
So this class is taught by--
it's a Comparative Media

00:00:41.880 --> 00:00:42.616
Studies course.

00:00:42.616 --> 00:00:44.740
So we'll be talking a lot
about the kinds of things

00:00:44.740 --> 00:00:46.510
that they talk about in
Comparative Media Studies.

00:00:46.510 --> 00:00:48.500
We'll study research
and design practices,

00:00:48.500 --> 00:00:51.030
but as it relates to
software engineering,

00:00:51.030 --> 00:00:54.070
and in particular to
developing video games-- so

00:00:54.070 --> 00:01:00.230
digital video games
for, basically, screens.

00:01:00.230 --> 00:01:03.700
The CMS department has a lot of
different, really cool research

00:01:03.700 --> 00:01:05.120
labs that are a part of it.

00:01:05.120 --> 00:01:06.770
And we are one of them.

00:01:06.770 --> 00:01:08.370
So we are the MIT Game Lab.

00:01:08.370 --> 00:01:11.240
Basically the whole
MIT Game Lab staff

00:01:11.240 --> 00:01:12.999
teaches this class together.

00:01:12.999 --> 00:01:15.290
Because we really like each
other, and it's really fun.

00:01:15.290 --> 00:01:16.670
But also because
there's a lot of you.

00:01:16.670 --> 00:01:18.753
And it's a really big,
complicated class to teach.

00:01:18.753 --> 00:01:20.900
So we need all the extra
support we can get.

00:01:20.900 --> 00:01:23.194
We teach classes in game
design and game research.

00:01:23.194 --> 00:01:25.360
Those are all the course
numbers that we teach other

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:26.540
than this one.

00:01:26.540 --> 00:01:28.210
Maybe you've taken
one of these before.

00:01:28.210 --> 00:01:30.120
Maybe you're thinking about
some other game courses

00:01:30.120 --> 00:01:31.580
you want to take in the future.

00:01:31.580 --> 00:01:32.780
So take a look at that.

00:01:32.780 --> 00:01:34.410
We also have UROP opportunities.

00:01:34.410 --> 00:01:38.040
So we'll advertise those
classes as they come up.

00:01:38.040 --> 00:01:41.380
We do mentor Course 6
students for the UAPs.

00:01:41.380 --> 00:01:43.050
What we usually ask
is for you to bring

00:01:43.050 --> 00:01:45.020
to us an interesting
research topic that you

00:01:45.020 --> 00:01:46.270
want to research.

00:01:46.270 --> 00:01:48.790
