00:23:07.640 --> 00:23:09.120
I just came from
the Lincoln Labs,

00:23:09.120 --> 00:23:11.820
where I'm collaborating with
MIT folks there as well.

00:23:11.820 --> 00:23:15.700
But most of my time, I work with
a humanitarian team-- the Red

00:23:15.700 --> 00:23:18.990
Cross/Red Crescent
Climate Centre.

00:23:18.990 --> 00:23:21.450
It's like a think tank within
the humanitarian sector.

00:23:21.450 --> 00:23:22.970
It's based in the Netherlands.

00:23:22.970 --> 00:23:26.120
We cover the planet--
187 countries.

00:23:26.120 --> 00:23:28.930
I am in charge of research,
in charge of innovation,

00:23:28.930 --> 00:23:30.860
mostly in charge of Africa.

00:23:30.860 --> 00:23:36.890
And unfortunately for the world,
we have way, way too much work.

00:23:36.890 --> 00:23:40.660
The workload is so
ridiculously huge

00:23:40.660 --> 00:23:43.760
that in my opinion,
especially coming from science

00:23:43.760 --> 00:23:47.800
and technology, we need
to change the way we

00:23:47.800 --> 00:23:50.860
think about humanitarian work.

00:23:50.860 --> 00:23:53.510
And if it is about
changing how we think,

00:23:53.510 --> 00:23:57.120
traditional ways are
not working too well.

00:23:57.120 --> 00:23:59.350
And that's why I'm here.

00:23:59.350 --> 00:24:01.400
I love this slide.

00:24:01.400 --> 00:24:04.190
We have a comfort zone,
which is doing things the way

00:24:04.190 --> 00:24:05.460
we've been doing them.

00:24:05.460 --> 00:24:06.270
Someone's hungry?

00:24:06.270 --> 00:24:07.050
Go get food.

00:24:07.050 --> 00:24:07.900
Someone's homeless?

00:24:07.900 --> 00:24:08.630
Go give shelter.

00:24:08.630 --> 00:24:10.120
Someone's sick?

00:24:10.120 --> 00:24:11.740
Help them heal.

00:24:11.740 --> 00:24:14.750
But we no longer have the
money, the brain power,

00:24:14.750 --> 00:24:17.460
the equipment to deal
with all that's happening.

00:24:17.460 --> 00:24:18.670
Too much is happening.

00:24:18.670 --> 00:24:20.480
The climate is changing.

00:24:20.480 --> 00:24:22.440
Environmental
degradation, urbanization,

00:24:22.440 --> 00:24:26.200
political instability, weird
diseases-- you name it.

00:24:26.200 --> 00:24:30.760
How can we learn more
about what we can do?

00:24:30.760 --> 00:24:36.300
We need as humanitarian
workers to get into a new place

00:24:36.300 --> 00:24:39.050
where we can do more
with what we have.

00:24:39.050 --> 00:24:41.590
And that place is
outside our comfort zone.

00:24:41.590 --> 00:24:44.030
Now magic can happen.

00:24:44.030 --> 00:24:46.295
But very often, we step
out of our comfort zone

00:24:46.295 --> 00:24:48.220
and we fall into the abyss.

00:24:48.220 --> 00:24:51.080
It's not easy to
find the right place.

00:24:51.080 --> 00:24:53.300
This is a risky endeavor for me.

00:24:53.300 --> 00:24:56.440
I'm here hoping
that you guys will

00:24:56.440 --> 00:24:59.030
accomplish one of two things.

00:24:59.030 --> 00:25:00.600
One is maybe you
come up with a game

00:25:00.600 --> 00:25:03.347
concept that has a life
after the end of your course.

00:25:03.347 --> 00:25:04.180
You get your credit.

00:25:04.180 --> 00:25:05.140
You graduate.

00:25:05.140 --> 00:25:07.210
And the Red Cross
or others can play

00:25:07.210 --> 00:25:09.110
a game that helps
someone understand

00:25:09.110 --> 00:25:11.300
something, helps
someone do something,

00:25:11.300 --> 00:25:13.690
helps someone collect
data about something.

00:25:13.690 --> 00:25:15.750
And we'll talk more about
what are those things

00:25:15.750 --> 00:25:19.420
that we want when we
get to project four.

00:25:19.420 --> 00:25:23.200
The other one is maybe we can
lure you-- even if one of you,

00:25:23.200 --> 00:25:26.090
even if one of the
Game Lab team--

00:25:26.090 --> 00:25:28.650
to consider humanitarian
work as part

00:25:28.650 --> 00:25:31.460
of what you may be doing
in your future life,

00:25:31.460 --> 00:25:35.080
either as your job,
or as your hobby.

00:25:35.080 --> 00:25:36.840
It's great fun.

00:25:36.840 --> 00:25:39.000
It's a great
intellectual challenge.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:41.850
The head of my team, Martin
[? Van Ahls-- ?] he's

00:25:41.850 --> 00:25:44.310
an astrophysicist by training.

00:25:44.310 --> 00:25:44.810
OK?

00:25:44.810 --> 00:25:49.140
So you don't have much
awareness of the extent

00:25:49.140 --> 00:25:52.440
to which humanitarian workers
can come from unusual places.

00:25:52.440 --> 00:25:55.760
And we hope that MIT stops
being an unusual place

00:25:55.760 --> 00:25:58.060
for humanitarian stuff.

00:25:58.060 --> 00:26:01.280
So let me illustrate the
kinds of challenges we get.

00:26:01.280 --> 00:26:05.510
This is an actual fax that
actually arrived in May,

00:26:05.510 --> 00:26:07.740
2008 to the office
of my colleague Yusef

00:26:07.740 --> 00:26:11.030
[? ayd-Shaloush, ?] who at
the time was based in Dakar.

00:26:13.730 --> 00:26:16.080
Let me see if this works.

00:26:16.080 --> 00:26:16.750
OK.

00:26:16.750 --> 00:26:21.410
For those of you who know Dakar,
it's near those green pixels.

00:26:21.410 --> 00:26:24.800
That's where, at the time,
the regional office was

00:26:24.800 --> 00:26:26.120
for West and Central Africa.

00:26:26.120 --> 00:26:30.320
28 countries going
from Mauritania--

00:26:30.320 --> 00:26:32.534
where there have
been a military coup,

00:26:32.534 --> 00:26:34.700
and there was bloodshed in
the streets and Red Cross

00:26:34.700 --> 00:26:37.810
volunteers needed to learn
first aid to prevent someone

00:26:37.810 --> 00:26:40.440
bleeding to death--
all the way to Congo

00:26:40.440 --> 00:26:43.780
Brazzaville in the southernmost
part of this area, where there

00:26:43.780 --> 00:26:46.380
was flooding-- urban flooding.

00:26:46.380 --> 00:26:48.710
And as Red Cross,
we don't fully know

00:26:48.710 --> 00:26:53.160
how to operate in rapidly
changing urban contexts.

00:26:53.160 --> 00:26:56.420
We're used to a planet where
poor, suffering people were

00:26:56.420 --> 00:26:58.830
either in conflict
or in rural areas.

00:26:58.830 --> 00:27:03.820
And Darfur-- people going to
Chad-- needing shelter, aid,

00:27:03.820 --> 00:27:05.090
all sorts of things.

00:27:05.090 --> 00:27:08.030
Yusef has to deal with
those three and everything

00:27:08.030 --> 00:27:11.360
in between-- chronic food
insecurity, Burkina Faso,

00:27:11.360 --> 00:27:14.010
you name it-- insufficient
training for his staff.

00:27:14.010 --> 00:27:17.380
And he gets this fax.

00:27:17.380 --> 00:27:22.050
Now I want you to think
you're a decision maker.

00:27:22.050 --> 00:27:25.520
You're someone who has to make
decisions and gets this fax.

00:27:25.520 --> 00:27:28.780
It was issued in May,
referring to the three coming

00:27:28.780 --> 00:27:31.020
months-- June, July, August.

00:27:31.020 --> 00:27:35.772
And it says if we define
an extreme precipitation

00:27:35.772 --> 00:27:37.230
event-- extreme
rainfall-- as being

00:27:37.230 --> 00:27:41.020
in the top 15% of the
historical record,

00:27:41.020 --> 00:27:43.040
then this year-- there
was a lot of text.

00:27:43.040 --> 00:27:44.380
I won't bother you with that.

00:27:44.380 --> 00:27:46.880
This year, because of sea
surface temperature anomalies

00:27:46.880 --> 00:27:49.980
and other things that maybe you
know if you're an MIT student,

00:27:49.980 --> 00:27:53.000
but it's not what we're
used to-- this year,

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:56.290
because of that stuff, the
probability of extreme rains

00:27:56.290 --> 00:28:01.970
is enhanced from 15%
to between 40% and 50%.

00:28:01.970 --> 00:28:03.780
So this fax is in the office.

00:28:03.780 --> 00:28:05.960
And Yusef looks at it.

00:28:05.960 --> 00:28:07.080
And what does he do?

00:28:07.080 --> 00:28:08.430
What do you think he does?

00:28:08.430 --> 00:28:11.120
What do you think the
humanitarian sector

00:28:11.120 --> 00:28:14.060
does when we get information?

00:28:14.060 --> 00:28:15.850
First of all, to
understand it fully

00:28:15.850 --> 00:28:18.980
you need to stop doing
everything else you're doing.

00:28:18.980 --> 00:28:20.550
You have to not answer an email.

00:28:20.550 --> 00:28:23.820
You have to not sign the check
for the fuel for the driver

00:28:23.820 --> 00:28:25.920
for delivering the
something or other.

00:28:25.920 --> 00:28:28.220
And once you start
thinking about it,

00:28:28.220 --> 00:28:30.610
what do I do with the
place with the green pixel?

00:28:30.610 --> 00:28:33.922
Do I send-- I don't
know, one tent?

00:28:33.922 --> 00:28:34.630
A thousand tents?

00:28:34.630 --> 00:28:36.616
Where do I send
them, and to do what?

00:28:36.616 --> 00:28:37.490
What are the chances?

00:28:37.490 --> 00:28:39.950
When will it happen?

00:28:39.950 --> 00:28:43.910
So my job is to
help the Red Cross

00:28:43.910 --> 00:28:45.550
family and the
humanitarian sector

00:28:45.550 --> 00:28:50.210
at large to understand science
that can help us make smarter

00:28:50.210 --> 00:28:51.980
decisions.

00:28:51.980 --> 00:28:56.730
Now if you want to
represent, to model,

00:28:56.730 --> 00:29:01.080
with an experience of forecast,
this is how it normally works.

00:29:01.080 --> 00:29:04.590
There's information that
allegedly can support action.

00:29:04.590 --> 00:29:07.890
That is communicated with an
audience in a passive mode,

00:29:07.890 --> 00:29:11.884
like a fax or an email or
a TV or radio announcement.

00:29:11.884 --> 00:29:13.300
And then you hope
that people will

00:29:13.300 --> 00:29:15.090
get it and do the right thing.

00:29:15.090 --> 00:29:17.735
Of course, I leave a question
mark, because-- not always?

00:29:20.670 --> 00:29:25.290
Now when I talked to people
about climate science--

00:29:25.290 --> 00:29:27.040
about changing
climate conditions;

00:29:27.040 --> 00:29:29.080
sea levels rise, so
we need new locations

00:29:29.080 --> 00:29:32.850
of shelters; about El Nino
and changing risks of drought

00:29:32.850 --> 00:29:35.860
and food insecurity;
about rainfall upstream,

00:29:35.860 --> 00:29:39.350
therefore flooding downstream--
I would be talking science.

00:29:39.350 --> 00:29:41.350
And the people I was
talking to-- they

00:29:41.350 --> 00:29:43.370
had something else to do.

00:29:43.370 --> 00:29:44.670
They had to go save lives.

00:29:44.670 --> 00:29:48.400
And they were forced into
a room just like you now.

00:29:48.400 --> 00:29:49.710
And I was talking science.

00:29:49.710 --> 00:29:54.120
And I could feel the extent
to which I was successfully

00:29:54.120 --> 00:29:55.560
shrinking their brains.

00:29:58.800 --> 00:30:00.120
This is a metaphor.

00:30:00.120 --> 00:30:02.300
There are very talented
and smart people

00:30:02.300 --> 00:30:03.710
in the humanitarian sector.

00:30:03.710 --> 00:30:07.560
But my putting them
into a passive mode,

00:30:07.560 --> 00:30:11.930
talking jargon to them, showing
maps and graphs and so on,

00:30:11.930 --> 00:30:13.550
was really not
accomplishing much.

00:30:13.550 --> 00:30:15.770
So I had to try something you.

00:30:15.770 --> 00:30:20.450
Oh, by the way, I remember
hearing the snoring

00:30:20.450 --> 00:30:23.080
while I was talking science.

00:30:23.080 --> 00:30:24.510
So it was shocking.

00:30:24.510 --> 00:30:27.840
Because they were wasting
their time listening to me

00:30:27.840 --> 00:30:30.800
unsuccessfully try to
communicate information

00:30:30.800 --> 00:30:32.760
that can help save lives.

00:30:32.760 --> 00:30:34.571
So I started doing other things.

00:30:34.571 --> 00:30:36.070
And we're going to
get a five minute

00:30:36.070 --> 00:30:38.280
flavor of the kind of
things we're doing.

00:30:38.280 --> 00:30:39.730
So let's play.

00:30:39.730 --> 00:30:42.160
You're a team.

00:30:42.160 --> 00:30:43.284
Split in half.

00:30:43.284 --> 00:30:45.700
Each one of you choose, are
you on this half or this half?

00:30:45.700 --> 00:30:46.283
You're a team.

00:30:46.283 --> 00:30:47.280
You're a team.

00:30:47.280 --> 00:30:49.370
You're a team-- four teams.

00:30:49.370 --> 00:30:52.020
There will be one winning team.

00:30:52.020 --> 00:30:54.880
The winning team
is the team that

00:30:54.880 --> 00:30:57.970
has the most people standing
by the end of the game.

00:30:57.970 --> 00:30:59.430
We'll have a few
practice rounds,

00:30:59.430 --> 00:31:01.580
and then we'll play for real.

00:31:01.580 --> 00:31:02.800
OK?

00:31:02.800 --> 00:31:04.250
You are not who
you think you are.

00:31:04.250 --> 00:31:06.820
You're not some MIT
student or something.

00:31:06.820 --> 00:31:10.780
You are magically, in the magic
circle of this game, a Red

00:31:10.780 --> 00:31:13.070
Cross disaster manager.

00:31:13.070 --> 00:31:13.771
OK?

00:31:13.771 --> 00:31:14.270
Good.

00:31:14.270 --> 00:31:16.910
Someone is celebrating.

00:31:16.910 --> 00:31:17.680
You're hired.

00:31:17.680 --> 00:31:20.740
We have no money,
but you're hired.

00:31:20.740 --> 00:31:24.930
So there are three kinds
of things you can do.

00:31:24.930 --> 00:31:27.230
And everyone will be standing
when the game begins.

00:31:27.230 --> 00:31:28.419
One is to go like this.

00:31:28.419 --> 00:31:29.960
This means I hope
there's good rains.

00:31:29.960 --> 00:31:31.918
I'm going to take advantage
of this opportunity

00:31:31.918 --> 00:31:34.270
to do good things when
there's good rains.

00:31:34.270 --> 00:31:35.040
Train people.

00:31:35.040 --> 00:31:36.590
Change the tires of the vehicle.

00:31:36.590 --> 00:31:38.010
Build a shelter.

00:31:38.010 --> 00:31:39.530
Write a proposal for donors.

00:31:39.530 --> 00:31:42.510
Write a report to the donor
that gave me money last year.

00:31:42.510 --> 00:31:45.630
All those things, you can
do when it's a nice day.

00:31:45.630 --> 00:31:48.520
Now maybe there's
too much rain coming.

00:31:48.520 --> 00:31:50.410
Then you can invest
in preparedness

00:31:50.410 --> 00:31:51.390
against too much rain.

00:31:51.390 --> 00:31:54.520
You make this gesture
like an umbrella.

00:31:54.520 --> 00:31:56.520
And it means you're
preparing against the risk

00:31:56.520 --> 00:31:57.490
of too much rain.

00:31:57.490 --> 00:32:00.130
This could be
prepositioning relief items,

00:32:00.130 --> 00:32:03.810
like tents, for those who have
to be displaced with the flood.

00:32:03.810 --> 00:32:05.680
But it's better to do
it before the flood.

00:32:05.680 --> 00:32:06.870
Because if you
wait for the flood,

00:32:06.870 --> 00:32:08.430
then the bridge has
been washed away.

00:32:08.430 --> 00:32:12.120
And you have no way to take
tents to the other side.

00:32:12.120 --> 00:32:16.460
The other option you have is
to do a bucket-- something

00:32:16.460 --> 00:32:18.160
to hold water from the sky.

00:32:18.160 --> 00:32:19.900
If there's a risk
of a drought, you

00:32:19.900 --> 00:32:21.690
want to collect water
