00:45:55.940 --> 00:45:59.990
What do we have, in terms
of skills and knowledge,

00:45:59.990 --> 00:46:04.180
in terms of equipment,
in terms of experience?

00:46:04.180 --> 00:46:08.330
The disease chikungunya--
has anyone heard of it?

00:46:08.330 --> 00:46:10.880
So what are you going to do
if an outbreak of chikungunya

00:46:10.880 --> 00:46:13.120
comes out to MIT tomorrow?

00:46:13.120 --> 00:46:13.620
Right?

00:46:13.620 --> 00:46:15.160
Knowing can help.

00:46:15.160 --> 00:46:18.210
Sensing can help you
make better decisions.

00:46:18.210 --> 00:46:22.300
In short, in my experience,
only games can do this.

00:46:22.300 --> 00:46:24.930
Only games can get a
bunch of people together,

00:46:24.930 --> 00:46:26.680
and in a very short
time understand

00:46:26.680 --> 00:46:29.430
the role of information in
the context of decisions

00:46:29.430 --> 00:46:31.490
that will have
consequences-- including

00:46:31.490 --> 00:46:34.990
lifesaving or
life-losing consequences.

00:46:34.990 --> 00:46:37.530
This is an example--
I'm going to skip it,

00:46:37.530 --> 00:46:38.674
so I can get to the end.

00:46:38.674 --> 00:46:40.090
But basically,
games can also help

00:46:40.090 --> 00:46:43.620
you collect data and compare
one scenario versus another,

00:46:43.620 --> 00:46:47.050
and see which are the things,
the aspects of the real world,

00:46:47.050 --> 00:46:50.600
where people are failing
to get something.

00:46:50.600 --> 00:46:52.550
And so you can
target your efforts

00:46:52.550 --> 00:46:54.610
in capacity-building
training, et cetera.

00:46:57.160 --> 00:46:59.950
This is one of the things
I will talk to you about.

00:46:59.950 --> 00:47:04.150
I will want you want to help
us design games or playful

00:47:04.150 --> 00:47:07.650
activities that can help people
make their decisions based

00:47:07.650 --> 00:47:10.570
on forecast, as
opposed to always doing

00:47:10.570 --> 00:47:12.840
as if it were the normal die.

00:47:12.840 --> 00:47:15.310
And then if there's a
flood, as the forecast said

00:47:15.310 --> 00:47:17.200
was more likely, you
go, eh, I don't know.

00:47:17.200 --> 00:47:18.300
I wasn't prepared.

00:47:18.300 --> 00:47:22.460
Which is what happens
quite frequently.

00:47:22.460 --> 00:47:23.979
There are many advantages.

00:47:23.979 --> 00:47:25.520
One is that we get
better performance

00:47:25.520 --> 00:47:28.040
in terms of outcomes--
fewer sick people.

00:47:28.040 --> 00:47:31.020
Better efficiency-- so you
save more per unit money

00:47:31.020 --> 00:47:33.100
or equipment or et cetera.

00:47:33.100 --> 00:47:35.110
Flexibility-- people
can do more if they

00:47:35.110 --> 00:47:36.594
understand the forecast.

00:47:36.594 --> 00:47:38.260
If you know that
Katrina is about to hit

00:47:38.260 --> 00:47:41.600
your village or
your city, there's

00:47:41.600 --> 00:47:43.970
more you can do in anticipation,
as opposed to waiting.

00:47:43.970 --> 00:47:46.370
And once it slams,
there's very few things

00:47:46.370 --> 00:47:47.760
you can do at that point.

00:47:47.760 --> 00:47:51.020
Because if you step out of
your door, you're in trouble.

00:47:51.020 --> 00:47:55.590
Games can create the
appetite, through confusion.

00:47:55.590 --> 00:47:59.280
With the cone, you
were like, huh?

00:47:59.280 --> 00:48:03.930
We deliberately
create systems that

00:48:03.930 --> 00:48:08.020
push people to the
tolerable edge of confusion.

00:48:08.020 --> 00:48:10.260
So that they want to
figure out, to make

00:48:10.260 --> 00:48:11.770
sense of what's going on.

00:48:11.770 --> 00:48:14.280
And then participants
themselves-- individually

00:48:14.280 --> 00:48:17.580
or in conversation with
peers, they go like, huh.

00:48:17.580 --> 00:48:19.470
So if we do this
and this happens,

00:48:19.470 --> 00:48:21.940
I'll be better off than
if I do this other thing.

00:48:21.940 --> 00:48:25.220
The aha moment-- the
epiphany, the revelation--

00:48:25.220 --> 00:48:27.720
is constructed by the players.

00:48:27.720 --> 00:48:30.040
And that has much
more lasting effect

00:48:30.040 --> 00:48:32.350
than if I give you the answer.

00:48:32.350 --> 00:48:36.740
No one remembers the answer if
no one was asking the question.

00:48:36.740 --> 00:48:41.900
Very few examples-- these
cones are the result

00:48:41.900 --> 00:48:45.784
of a collaboration with the
World Bank Chief Economist

00:48:45.784 --> 00:48:46.950
for Sustainable Development.

00:48:46.950 --> 00:48:50.510
He was trying to explain
a confusing concept called

00:48:50.510 --> 00:48:51.239
deep uncertainty.

00:48:51.239 --> 00:48:52.780
[? Jana ?] over
there-- can you wave,

00:48:52.780 --> 00:48:55.900
[? Jana? ?] She's my partner in
game design, and facilitation,

00:48:55.900 --> 00:48:56.400
and life.

00:48:56.400 --> 00:48:59.340
She had the brilliant idea of
taking-- our cone had surgery.

00:48:59.340 --> 00:48:59.840
Sorry.

00:48:59.840 --> 00:49:01.650
Our cat had surgery.

00:49:01.650 --> 00:49:05.220
And she thought, how about
using the cone of shame--

00:49:05.220 --> 00:49:08.650
you know, for the creature not
to lick its surgery-- she said,

00:49:08.650 --> 00:49:12.040
how about using that for
depicting this uncertainty?

00:49:12.040 --> 00:49:15.680
Now we had students tossing
each one of those cones

00:49:15.680 --> 00:49:17.840
100 times to see the
probability solution,

00:49:17.840 --> 00:49:20.851
with and without
spin, and augmenting

00:49:20.851 --> 00:49:22.600
the gap between what
you think will happen

00:49:22.600 --> 00:49:24.480
and what actually happens.

00:49:24.480 --> 00:49:28.060
A few other cases-- this
is from Hanoi University

00:49:28.060 --> 00:49:29.210
of Science and Technology.

00:49:29.210 --> 00:49:33.470
These was with 350 students
playing a game on dengue.

00:49:33.470 --> 00:49:35.075
It's like a rock
paper scissors, where

00:49:35.075 --> 00:49:36.390
three players are mosquitoes.

00:49:36.390 --> 00:49:40.100
And they can either bite, or
with your blood, lay eggs.

00:49:40.100 --> 00:49:41.980
And the other
players are humans.

00:49:41.980 --> 00:49:44.950
And they can either
protect from biting

00:49:44.950 --> 00:49:46.820
or attack the breeding grounds.

00:49:46.820 --> 00:49:51.630
This was designed by students
at game design students

00:49:51.630 --> 00:49:54.060
at [? Parsons ?] and
professors collaborating

00:49:54.060 --> 00:49:56.380
with the other students.

00:49:56.380 --> 00:50:00.990
This one is a
publication from NASA.

00:50:00.990 --> 00:50:04.040
It doesn't get more NASA
than a rocket launch.

00:50:04.040 --> 00:50:07.510
But if you look here, it says,
Erin Coughlan-- former intern

00:50:07.510 --> 00:50:09.340
and now staff in my team.

00:50:09.340 --> 00:50:11.820
And the Red Cross/Red Crescent
Climate Centre project.

00:50:11.820 --> 00:50:17.350
You go to page 47, and you
see [? Munu. ?] [? Munu ?] is

00:50:17.350 --> 00:50:20.000
a volunteer of the
Zambia Red Cross,

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:24.810
from the village of Kazungula
in Western Zambia on the Zambezi

00:50:24.810 --> 00:50:26.750
River.

00:50:26.750 --> 00:50:30.180
I mean, there's not much
electricity or NASA-ness

00:50:30.180 --> 00:50:31.520
in Kazungula.

00:50:31.520 --> 00:50:35.810
But he was trained as a
facilitator for a game

00:50:35.810 --> 00:50:37.860
where, with cards
and dice, there's

00:50:37.860 --> 00:50:40.020
rain that happens over there.

00:50:40.020 --> 00:50:42.650
So her cup gets some water.

00:50:42.650 --> 00:50:44.850
And then from her cup,
she passes the water

00:50:44.850 --> 00:50:47.900
to the person next to her,
representing the upstream going

00:50:47.900 --> 00:50:48.650
downstream.

00:50:48.650 --> 00:50:50.570
She can get more water or not.

00:50:50.570 --> 00:50:52.100
And it keeps going
until maybe he

00:50:52.100 --> 00:50:54.350
gets water to overflow his cup.

00:50:54.350 --> 00:50:57.820
He's in trouble, unless he
takes some action ahead of time.

00:50:57.820 --> 00:51:00.720
And the game we're
designing is not only

00:51:00.720 --> 00:51:03.520
with cups and to mimic
the upstream/downstream.

00:51:03.520 --> 00:51:06.710
But we're also making a digital
game where people actually

00:51:06.710 --> 00:51:08.900
monitor river levels.

00:51:08.900 --> 00:51:10.450
And they make predictions.

00:51:10.450 --> 00:51:15.010
They make bets as to what the
river level will be in two days

00:51:15.010 --> 00:51:16.170
or so.

00:51:16.170 --> 00:51:17.680
And then the winner wins points.

00:51:17.680 --> 00:51:20.800
But they can use points to
buy information from upstream.

00:51:20.800 --> 00:51:24.310
And then with that data we're
developing a hydrological model

00:51:24.310 --> 00:51:27.690
that can help us better know
what is going down the stream,

00:51:27.690 --> 00:51:31.310
and are we going to
have more flood trouble?

00:51:31.310 --> 00:51:35.170
As you can imagine, it's
awesome to have NASA report

00:51:35.170 --> 00:51:39.180
on some little project in
Western Zambia, in part

00:51:39.180 --> 00:51:41.060
because we know
that we can partner

00:51:41.060 --> 00:51:43.600
these on-the-field
game-based data

00:51:43.600 --> 00:51:48.120
collection with satellite image
for ground truthing and so on.

00:51:48.120 --> 00:51:51.870
This one-- because we
are being recorded,

00:51:51.870 --> 00:51:54.840
I will not disclose
the full story.

00:51:54.840 --> 00:51:58.590
But in short, we play the
game that had the same story.

00:51:58.590 --> 00:51:59.890
You play with a 6-sided die.

00:51:59.890 --> 00:52:01.530
You know your probabilities.

00:52:01.530 --> 00:52:04.160
It was being played with
the top-level climate

00:52:04.160 --> 00:52:06.295
scientists in this planet.

00:52:06.295 --> 00:52:07.920
And as you can see
on the left, there's

00:52:07.920 --> 00:52:10.440
all sorts of calculations
with probability distributions

00:52:10.440 --> 00:52:11.880
and the cost benefits and so on.

00:52:11.880 --> 00:52:14.470
Then we change the
probabilities on them.

00:52:14.470 --> 00:52:16.870
And then we gave them that.

00:52:16.870 --> 00:52:18.536
Just like you were
saying, what is that?

00:52:18.536 --> 00:52:19.619
What are you going to use?

00:52:19.619 --> 00:52:22.350
We just gave them that
graph and the caption.

00:52:22.350 --> 00:52:24.766
And some of them were
saying, but wait a second.

00:52:24.766 --> 00:52:26.390
Why are you giving
me this information?

00:52:26.390 --> 00:52:29.310
It's completely useless in
the context of my decision

00:52:29.310 --> 00:52:30.640
situation.

00:52:30.640 --> 00:52:33.100
And then we told them,
this is the information

00:52:33.100 --> 00:52:36.900
that you yourselves produced
in the summary for policymakers

00:52:36.900 --> 00:52:39.040
of climate science stuff.

00:52:39.040 --> 00:52:42.280
And they became fully
aware of the need

00:52:42.280 --> 00:52:46.040
for them to improve the way they
communicate climate science.

00:52:49.350 --> 00:52:52.130
This-- you may
recognize that dude.

00:52:52.130 --> 00:52:54.600
I think it's the last time I
wore a necktie-- at the White

00:52:54.600 --> 00:52:56.460
House.

00:52:56.460 --> 00:52:57.880
I was given five minutes.

00:52:57.880 --> 00:52:59.840
I begged for seven.

00:52:59.840 --> 00:53:03.910
Seven minutes given, preceded
by extensive PowerPoint

00:53:03.910 --> 00:53:06.450
presentations or other
forms of uni-directional,

00:53:06.450 --> 00:53:11.352
so I had an audience that had
brain wave activity declining.

00:53:11.352 --> 00:53:12.060
And I said hello.

00:53:12.060 --> 00:53:12.940
My name is Pablo.

00:53:12.940 --> 00:53:14.180
And this is not a Frisbee.

00:53:14.180 --> 00:53:15.030
It's a hurricane.

00:53:15.030 --> 00:53:17.684
Everybody stand up.

00:53:17.684 --> 00:53:19.100
And people were
somewhat confused.

00:53:19.100 --> 00:53:19.910
Some were standing.

00:53:19.910 --> 00:53:22.118
Others were distracted, and
they saw people standing,

00:53:22.118 --> 00:53:22.833
so they stood.

00:53:22.833 --> 00:53:23.300
And I said, OK.

00:53:23.300 --> 00:53:25.383
I'm going to throw this
frisbee in some direction.

00:53:25.383 --> 00:53:26.120
It's a hurricane.

00:53:26.120 --> 00:53:29.010
If it hits you in the
chest, it's trouble.

00:53:29.010 --> 00:53:30.520
You're suffering.

00:53:30.520 --> 00:53:34.430
Now if you sit down, it will
fly above your head, no problem.

00:53:34.430 --> 00:53:35.786
It's like evacuation.

00:53:35.786 --> 00:53:37.160
But if you sit
down and evacuate,

00:53:37.160 --> 00:53:39.640
and the hurricane goes
in some other direction,

00:53:39.640 --> 00:53:41.390
someone may still
your refrigerator.

00:53:41.390 --> 00:53:43.040
Right?

00:53:43.040 --> 00:53:45.130
You're doing the wrong thing.

00:53:45.130 --> 00:53:48.800
So where it will go will be
determined by these two dice.

00:53:48.800 --> 00:53:51.710
So you either say standing
or sit down to avoid it.

00:53:51.710 --> 00:53:53.170
And I throw the things.

00:53:53.170 --> 00:53:53.790
And I look.

00:53:53.790 --> 00:53:55.984
And I throw in this direction
and in this direction.

00:53:55.984 --> 00:53:56.900
People were being hit.

00:53:56.900 --> 00:53:58.120
There was huge confusion.

00:53:58.120 --> 00:54:00.050
No one understood
what was going on.

00:54:00.050 --> 00:54:01.990
And then someone got it.

00:54:01.990 --> 00:54:03.280
Double one, I throw over here.

00:54:03.280 --> 00:54:05.000
Double six, I throw over here.

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:06.680
Interpolate.

00:54:06.680 --> 00:54:07.764
So someone figured it out.

00:54:07.764 --> 00:54:08.679
They said, oh, a nine!

00:54:08.679 --> 00:54:10.030
It will go in that direction.

00:54:10.030 --> 00:54:11.590
Everybody sat down.

00:54:11.590 --> 00:54:12.590
And I threw the frisbee.

00:54:12.590 --> 00:54:15.000
And it flew elegantly
until it hit

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:16.910
the wall of the White House.

00:54:16.910 --> 00:54:19.720
And then I said, well,
you know, climate science

00:54:19.720 --> 00:54:21.290
can give us this.

00:54:21.290 --> 00:54:22.330
Think Katrina.

00:54:22.330 --> 00:54:24.090
Think all that we could do.

00:54:24.090 --> 00:54:25.310
We're here to help.

00:54:25.310 --> 00:54:26.210
Thank you.

00:54:26.210 --> 00:54:28.760
And that game was memorable.

00:54:28.760 --> 00:54:29.830
It opened doors.

00:54:29.830 --> 00:54:32.270
And it created
awareness of the value

00:54:32.270 --> 00:54:34.160
of linking climate
science with decisions

00:54:34.160 --> 00:54:37.120
of the humanitarian sector,
of the government sector,

00:54:37.120 --> 00:54:38.660
and beyond.

00:54:38.660 --> 00:54:43.210
So game play beats
PowerPoint in a million ways.

00:54:43.210 --> 00:54:46.070
For me, as someone who has
to help others take actions

00:54:46.070 --> 00:54:48.390
that save lives, I'd
say first of all,

00:54:48.390 --> 00:54:49.740
there's active learning.

00:54:49.740 --> 00:54:53.080
When you were playing, and you
were confronted with that fax,

00:54:53.080 --> 00:54:54.490
you were saying, what is that?

00:54:54.490 --> 00:54:55.400
What does it mean?

00:54:55.400 --> 00:54:57.300
And what should I do about it?

00:54:57.300 --> 00:54:59.080
It's about action.

00:54:59.080 --> 00:55:01.590
And there's plenty of peer
to peer-- no, but look!

00:55:01.590 --> 00:55:03.910
If it's 50%-- and people
learn from each other.

00:55:03.910 --> 00:55:07.880
There are plenty
of "aha" moments.

00:55:07.880 --> 00:55:09.280
It's fun, but it's serious.

00:55:09.280 --> 00:55:11.390
And the fact that
it's fun is important.

00:55:11.390 --> 00:55:14.050
Neuroscientists, including
some in this building--

00:55:14.050 --> 00:55:18.050
I think Satra works
here-- have evidence

00:55:18.050 --> 00:55:19.840
that if you are
emotionally engaged,

00:55:19.840 --> 00:55:24.440
your learning goes
deeper and lasts longer.

00:55:24.440 --> 00:55:26.420
There is also the
ability to collect data.

00:55:26.420 --> 00:55:27.350
I didn't go into it.

00:55:27.350 --> 00:55:29.900
But that's one of the things
I'd be keen on using with you,

00:55:29.900 --> 00:55:32.380
if you are able to make
a digital game that

00:55:32.380 --> 00:55:35.100
can collect data and help us
understand, what do people

00:55:35.100 --> 00:55:35.600
know?

00:55:35.600 --> 00:55:36.474
What do people think?

00:55:36.474 --> 00:55:38.795
What do people want?

00:55:38.795 --> 00:55:40.920
And then we can use it as
an optimization platform.

00:55:40.920 --> 00:55:42.190
How much should we do?

00:55:42.190 --> 00:55:44.180
How many people should
stand up next time

00:55:44.180 --> 00:55:46.760
we have that forecast?

00:55:46.760 --> 00:55:48.859
It's like a Monte Carlo
simulation, right?

00:55:48.859 --> 00:55:49.900
You do things many times.

00:55:49.900 --> 00:55:51.690
And you figure out,
what are the things

00:55:51.690 --> 00:55:55.270
that you call optimal, based
on objective or subjective

00:55:55.270 --> 00:55:56.370
metrics?

00:55:56.370 --> 00:55:58.495
That's the website for my
team-- climatecentre.org.

00:56:01.050 --> 00:56:04.190
Note the British spelling.

00:56:04.190 --> 00:56:07.430
This is at the core--
why we love games.

00:56:07.430 --> 00:56:09.660
There's an
experiential learning.

00:56:09.660 --> 00:56:12.540
That's from our conversation
with your colleagues

00:56:12.540 --> 00:56:13.630
at the Lincoln Lab.

00:56:13.630 --> 00:56:17.430
You want to do things,
reflect what would happen,

00:56:17.430 --> 00:56:19.900
form abstract concepts--
maybe I should do this

00:56:19.900 --> 00:56:22.960
or that-- test it, and do
it again in a better way.

00:56:22.960 --> 00:56:24.890
And it's much safer to
do this in game play

00:56:24.890 --> 00:56:27.350
than to do it in the real
world, where if you fail,

00:56:27.350 --> 00:56:28.915
you can fail soundly.

00:56:28.915 --> 00:56:31.040
These are some of the
partners we have worked with,

