So in short, I wish you all
the best-- learning a lot

00:57:20.920 --> 00:57:24.900
from these guys, doing a
lot based on what you learn,

00:57:24.900 --> 00:57:26.850
and your own motivations.

00:57:26.850 --> 00:57:28.880
And whether you like
it or not, project four

00:57:28.880 --> 00:57:31.010
will involve doing
something for us.

00:57:31.010 --> 00:57:33.671
Thank you in advance for
accepting those rules.

00:57:33.671 --> 00:57:34.670
And there shall be more.

00:57:34.670 --> 00:57:36.270
Thank you very much.

00:57:36.270 --> 00:57:40.440
Oh and by the way, I will
leave this with you guys.

00:57:40.440 --> 00:57:44.550
It's our publication--
a shared endeavor

00:57:44.550 --> 00:57:48.040
of my Red Cross team and Boston
University Pardee Center.

00:57:48.040 --> 00:57:50.210
It's called, "Games
for a New Climate--

00:57:50.210 --> 00:57:53.600
Experiencing the Complexity
of Future Risks."

00:57:53.600 --> 00:57:55.940
I promise you it's fun to read.

00:57:55.940 --> 00:57:58.365
And it's available
online for free as a pdf.

00:57:58.365 --> 00:58:00.490
ANDREW GRANT: I'm going to
talk about game engines.

00:58:00.490 --> 00:58:01.670
And before I do, if
you want to think

00:58:01.670 --> 00:58:03.380
a little bit about one of the
things that Pablo was saying.

00:58:03.380 --> 00:58:04.990
It's about, one of the
things that a game does

00:58:04.990 --> 00:58:07.656
is it forces you to look at what
happened, and sort of say, huh?

00:58:07.656 --> 00:58:09.650
You figure out why
did that happen.

00:58:09.650 --> 00:58:11.209
And then you try to fix it.

00:58:11.209 --> 00:58:12.750
And that's actually
one of the things

00:58:12.750 --> 00:58:14.620
I think is very much
like programming.

00:58:14.620 --> 00:58:17.636
If you're trying to write
code, and something goes wrong,

00:58:17.636 --> 00:58:19.760
often that's what the
process of debugging is like.

00:58:19.760 --> 00:58:22.360
You go, why did the
screen flip upside down?

00:58:22.360 --> 00:58:23.425
That just makes no sense.

00:58:23.425 --> 00:58:24.800
And then you have
the aha moment.

00:58:24.800 --> 00:58:26.520
And you can go and fix it.

00:58:26.520 --> 00:58:30.922
Turns out that making software
is a lot like playing a game.

00:58:30.922 --> 00:58:33.380
So anyway, we're going to talk
about game engine selection.

00:58:33.380 --> 00:58:35.622
Because one of your early
tasks will be to sort of

00:58:35.622 --> 00:58:36.550
try out a game engine.

00:58:36.550 --> 00:58:38.700
We're not going to be using a
game engine for the first game

00:58:38.700 --> 00:58:39.395
project.

00:58:39.395 --> 00:58:40.845
But we want you
to be ready for it

00:58:40.845 --> 00:58:42.053
when it comes to project two.

00:58:44.880 --> 00:58:46.320
Now the first
thing to realize is

00:58:46.320 --> 00:58:50.441
that digital games are
basically a software project.

00:58:50.441 --> 00:58:51.940
They share a lot
of things in common

00:58:51.940 --> 00:58:53.440
with software in general.

00:58:53.440 --> 00:58:56.024
You're going to have a UI that
your user has to interact with.

00:58:56.024 --> 00:58:58.398
There's going to be something
going on in the background.

00:58:58.398 --> 00:58:59.900
For a commercial
or business offer,

00:58:59.900 --> 00:59:02.205
it might be a
database or something.

00:59:02.205 --> 00:59:04.330
There's probably going to
be either a design you're

00:59:04.330 --> 00:59:04.890
working from.

00:59:04.890 --> 00:59:05.849
Or you're making it up.

00:59:05.849 --> 00:59:07.265
Or maybe you've
got a customer who

00:59:07.265 --> 00:59:08.520
cares about what's going on.

00:59:08.520 --> 00:59:09.550
You've got features.

00:59:09.550 --> 00:59:10.340
You've got bugs.

00:59:10.340 --> 00:59:11.230
We've got task lists.

00:59:11.230 --> 00:59:13.790
All of the same sort
of managementy things

00:59:13.790 --> 00:59:16.980
that happen, happen on software
projects and game projects

00:59:16.980 --> 00:59:18.225
the same way.

00:59:18.225 --> 00:59:20.100
There's a little bit of
a difference, though.

00:59:20.100 --> 00:59:22.975
Games are a little bit
harder in some ways,

00:59:22.975 --> 00:59:23.850
and easier in others.

00:59:23.850 --> 00:59:24.340
But we're going to
talk about the ways

00:59:24.340 --> 00:59:27.130
that they're harder, because
that's more interesting.

00:59:27.130 --> 00:59:30.109
The thing that happens with
most business software-- or even

00:59:30.109 --> 00:59:31.150
something like Photoshop.

00:59:31.150 --> 00:59:32.780
Have any of you used Photoshop?

00:59:32.780 --> 00:59:33.599
Excellent.

00:59:33.599 --> 00:59:35.390
Photoshop is one of
those software packages

00:59:35.390 --> 00:59:39.050
that-- a lot of people like
to take classes in Photoshop

00:59:39.050 --> 00:59:40.841
before they get started.

00:59:40.841 --> 00:59:42.590
If you sat down to
Photoshop, you probably

00:59:42.590 --> 00:59:45.360
didn't think to yourself,
wow, this is easy.

00:59:45.360 --> 00:59:46.780
And if you did, wow.

00:59:46.780 --> 00:59:51.620
But basically, Photoshop has
hundreds, or perhaps even

00:59:51.620 --> 00:59:54.180
thousands, of features in
there that you don't know about

00:59:54.180 --> 00:59:55.250
until you've taken the classes.

00:59:55.250 --> 00:59:56.875
And if you want to
figure out something

00:59:56.875 --> 00:59:59.450
about Photoshop, your best bet,
really, is to go to a search

00:59:59.450 --> 00:59:59.870
prompt.

00:59:59.870 --> 01:00:02.411
And go to your favorite search
engine to find out what to do.

01:00:02.411 --> 01:00:03.620
Or ask someone who knows.

01:00:03.620 --> 01:00:05.161
Because actually
trying to figure out

01:00:05.161 --> 01:00:09.430
Photoshop from first principles
is really, really, really hard.

01:00:09.430 --> 01:00:11.790
The thing is that with a
game, you can't do that.

01:00:11.790 --> 01:00:13.100
You can't get away with that.

01:00:13.100 --> 01:00:15.720
If your game is
complex, no one's

01:00:15.720 --> 01:00:18.679
going to take a training class
to learn how to play your game.

01:00:18.679 --> 01:00:20.220
Now it might be the
case that someone

01:00:20.220 --> 01:00:22.680
will look at a walkthrough
or a cheat sheet or something

01:00:22.680 --> 01:00:25.370
to play your game-- after
they've played for three hours

01:00:25.370 --> 01:00:26.890
and decided they liked it.

01:00:26.890 --> 01:00:29.090
But they're not going
to do that first.

01:00:29.090 --> 01:00:31.285
That's a general, broad,
sweeping generalization.

01:00:31.285 --> 01:00:32.910
There are some people
that like nothing

01:00:32.910 --> 01:00:34.670
more than to read the
manual for a game.

01:00:34.670 --> 01:00:36.730
They mostly died out
about 10 years ago.

01:00:36.730 --> 01:00:38.910
But there are still
some hanging on.

01:00:38.910 --> 01:00:42.460
Generally speaking, nowadays,
you're going to play the game,

01:00:42.460 --> 01:00:44.230
and then you're going
to decide if you're

01:00:44.230 --> 01:00:45.864
going to read the
instructions or not.

01:00:45.864 --> 01:00:48.030
And this is going to be
true for your games as well.

01:00:48.030 --> 01:00:50.310
So your UI task-- your
user interaction piece

01:00:50.310 --> 01:00:52.330
for your game-- is
going to be hard.

01:00:52.330 --> 01:00:54.820
And the only way to make
sure that works properly

01:00:54.820 --> 01:00:58.590
is to test it over and over
again, as early as possible.

01:00:58.590 --> 01:01:00.090
So that's one way
in which games are

01:01:00.090 --> 01:01:03.680
going to be a little bit
harder than normal software.

01:01:03.680 --> 01:01:06.320
Also, games have to be fun.

01:01:06.320 --> 01:01:08.270
And we use the word
fun kind of loosely.

01:01:08.270 --> 01:01:09.780
And we're always scared
of using the word fun.

01:01:09.780 --> 01:01:11.190
Because there are serious games.

01:01:11.190 --> 01:01:13.314
There are games that are
supposed to make you think

01:01:13.314 --> 01:01:15.470
instead of get a big
smile on your face.

01:01:15.470 --> 01:01:18.510
But what they have to be is
engaging, or interesting.

01:01:18.510 --> 01:01:19.890
Photoshop's not a great example.

01:01:19.890 --> 01:01:22.320
If you're playing with
Photoshop as an undergrad,

01:01:22.320 --> 01:01:24.740
you're probably thinking to
yourself, this is kind of fun.

01:01:24.740 --> 01:01:28.640
But if you're using a fancy
piece of software for work,

01:01:28.640 --> 01:01:30.590
you're not doing that
because it's fun.

01:01:30.590 --> 01:01:33.330
You're probably doing it because
someone's paying you to do it.

01:01:33.330 --> 01:01:36.325
The games-- not so much.

01:01:36.325 --> 01:01:38.700
People are going to play it
because they want to play it,

01:01:38.700 --> 01:01:40.180
and for really no other reason.

01:01:40.180 --> 01:01:41.720
So your game has to be fun.

01:01:41.720 --> 01:01:44.130
And what you think is fun
they may not think is fun.

01:01:44.130 --> 01:01:45.440
So the only way to make
sure that your game is fun

01:01:45.440 --> 01:01:46.950
is to find some
users really quick,

01:01:46.950 --> 01:01:50.371
and try out your game on them
as soon as you possibly can.

01:01:50.371 --> 01:01:52.620
The same thing happens with
your game play difficulty.

01:01:52.620 --> 01:01:54.220
By the time you're
done with your game,

01:01:54.220 --> 01:01:56.053
you're going to think
the game was too easy.

01:01:56.053 --> 01:01:56.720
I guarantee it.

01:01:56.720 --> 01:01:58.090
And everyone who plays
it for the first time

01:01:58.090 --> 01:01:59.131
will think it's too hard.

01:01:59.131 --> 01:02:01.270
I guarantee that, too.

01:02:01.270 --> 01:02:04.050
So you have to test it with
other users, not yourselves.

01:02:04.050 --> 01:02:06.250
Because you will think
your game is too easy.

01:02:06.250 --> 01:02:08.810
And you'll be wrong.

01:02:08.810 --> 01:02:10.790
And then, of course,
finally, your game

01:02:10.790 --> 01:02:12.291
may have an impact
you want to have.

01:02:12.291 --> 01:02:14.165
And I'm going to keep
saying this over again.

01:02:14.165 --> 01:02:15.860
You're going to have
to test your game.

01:02:15.860 --> 01:02:18.540
Remember, there's a theme that's
going to keep going on here.

01:02:18.540 --> 01:02:19.960
And we're going to use
this theme with absolutely

01:02:19.960 --> 01:02:20.730
everything we do.

01:02:20.730 --> 01:02:22.360
When you're playing a
game, you try something.

01:02:22.360 --> 01:02:22.910
It doesn't work.

01:02:22.910 --> 01:02:23.701
You think about it.

01:02:23.701 --> 01:02:24.760
You try something new.

01:02:24.760 --> 01:02:26.480
When you're developing a game,
you're going to try something.

01:02:26.480 --> 01:02:27.438
It's not going to work.

01:02:27.438 --> 01:02:28.360
You try something new.

01:02:28.360 --> 01:02:30.810
When you're trying to make your
team work smoothly together,

01:02:30.810 --> 01:02:31.680
you're going to try something.

01:02:31.680 --> 01:02:32.800
And that's not going to work.

01:02:32.800 --> 01:02:33.950
And you'll try something new.

01:02:33.950 --> 01:02:36.340
We're going to talk about that
circle over and over and over

01:02:36.340 --> 01:02:37.131
again in the class.

01:02:37.131 --> 01:02:40.140
Because it works.

01:02:40.140 --> 01:02:45.620
So moving on, we're going
to talk about game engines.

01:02:45.620 --> 01:02:48.300
And if I talk to
quickly, as I have

01:02:48.300 --> 01:02:51.140
a habit of doing-- even more
so when I'm talking to people--

01:02:51.140 --> 01:02:52.586
let me know.

01:02:52.586 --> 01:02:53.460
Tell me to slow down.

01:02:57.760 --> 01:03:03.586
So this is the game
you want to make.

01:03:03.586 --> 01:03:04.210
It's beautiful.

01:03:07.080 --> 01:03:09.935
This is the tools
you have to make it.

01:03:09.935 --> 01:03:12.884
[LAUGHTER]

01:03:12.884 --> 01:03:15.300
ANDREW GRANT: So obviously,
what you're really going to do

01:03:15.300 --> 01:03:18.900
is going to be somewhere in
between these two extremes.

01:03:18.900 --> 01:03:20.790
And you have to think
really hard about how

01:03:20.790 --> 01:03:22.200
you're going to accomplish it.

01:03:22.200 --> 01:03:24.290
The vast majority of game
developers, especially

01:03:24.290 --> 01:03:26.165
new ones, are going to
come into it thinking,

01:03:26.165 --> 01:03:29.064
this is the awesome, perfect
thing I want to create.

01:03:29.064 --> 01:03:30.980
And then they're going
to come to their tools.

01:03:30.980 --> 01:03:33.970
And they're going to discover
that it's really hard to do.

01:03:33.970 --> 01:03:36.020
And so I encourage you--
rather than thinking

01:03:36.020 --> 01:03:39.290
of the big vision of
what you want to make,

01:03:39.290 --> 01:03:41.560
and then figuring
out how to get there,

01:03:41.560 --> 01:03:44.670
I recommend thinking
about what you've got.

01:03:44.670 --> 01:03:48.730
And then figure out,
what can you make?

01:03:48.730 --> 01:03:50.910
Now these are a couple
things you can do here.

01:03:50.910 --> 01:03:53.410
One, reduce in
your mind the scope

01:03:53.410 --> 01:03:54.960
of the thing you're
going to make.

01:03:54.960 --> 01:03:58.340
You're not going to
make your favorite RPG.

01:03:58.340 --> 01:04:01.010
You're not going to make an MMO.

01:04:01.010 --> 01:04:03.140
If you try, we
will laugh at you.

01:04:08.712 --> 01:04:10.670
You will occasionally
think about this top row.

01:04:10.670 --> 01:04:11.930
How do I get the awesome thing?

01:04:11.930 --> 01:04:13.679
But I really want to
encourage you instead

01:04:13.679 --> 01:04:15.720
to think, as much
as you possibly can,

01:04:15.720 --> 01:04:16.970
this is what I know how to do.

01:04:16.970 --> 01:04:18.470
These are the tools I have.

01:04:18.470 --> 01:04:21.020
What awesome thing can
I do with these tools?

01:04:21.020 --> 01:04:24.301
Rather than, how do I get over
there when I'm way over here

01:04:24.301 --> 01:04:24.800
right now?

01:04:30.270 --> 01:04:33.120
This is a quote
from a discussion

01:04:33.120 --> 01:04:36.200
I had with a game
team once where

01:04:36.200 --> 01:04:38.650
we were talking about a
particular technical problem.

01:04:38.650 --> 01:04:39.980
And I said, how hard is that?

01:04:39.980 --> 01:04:42.010
And the developer
says, well, it's

01:04:42.010 --> 01:04:43.660
really hard because of this,
that, and the other thing.

01:04:43.660 --> 01:04:43.860
I said, wait.

01:04:43.860 --> 01:04:44.500
Stop.

01:04:44.500 --> 01:04:46.040
Actually I didn't mean that.

01:04:46.040 --> 01:04:47.680
I don't care how hard it is.

01:04:47.680 --> 01:04:49.889
What I want to know is, how
long is it going to take?

01:04:49.889 --> 01:04:52.096
And we're going to say that
a lot in this class, too.

01:04:52.096 --> 01:04:53.890
We're going to say,
how hard is something?

01:04:53.890 --> 01:04:56.132
And often what we
really mean is,

01:04:56.132 --> 01:04:57.340
how long is it going to take?

01:04:57.340 --> 01:04:58.780
Because we don't
care if it takes

01:04:58.780 --> 01:05:01.580
an hour of really hard
thinking, to some extent.

01:05:01.580 --> 01:05:04.040
What we care is that
it takes an hour.

01:05:04.040 --> 01:05:05.620
If it's going to
take you an hour

01:05:05.620 --> 01:05:09.775
to do an easy thing-- like
sort a bunch of yellow stickers

01:05:09.775 --> 01:05:11.650
and a bunch of orange
stickers because that's

01:05:11.650 --> 01:05:12.972
part of your game prototype.

01:05:12.972 --> 01:05:14.930
If it takes an hour to
do that, that's an hour.

01:05:14.930 --> 01:05:16.721
It doesn't matter that
that's an easy task.

01:05:16.721 --> 01:05:17.270
That's time.

01:05:17.270 --> 01:05:18.686
And you have to
be careful how you

01:05:18.686 --> 01:05:20.989
spend your time in this
class-- actually, through all

01:05:20.989 --> 01:05:22.280
your classes at MIT, I suspect.

01:05:22.280 --> 01:05:24.140
But in this class,
we know that you

01:05:24.140 --> 01:05:27.370
don't have enough time
to get done every thing

01:05:27.370 --> 01:05:28.760
that you want to get done.

01:05:28.760 --> 01:05:30.384
And so you have to
think very carefully

01:05:30.384 --> 01:05:32.516
about how you spend your time.

01:05:32.516 --> 01:05:35.690
It turns out that game
development is already hard.

01:05:35.690 --> 01:05:37.800
You don't need to
add hard stuff to it.

01:05:40.820 --> 01:05:43.680
So a lot of what we're going to
focus on with choosing a game

01:05:43.680 --> 01:05:46.000
engine and all the
decisions you make is you

01:05:46.000 --> 01:05:49.050
want to write as little
code as possible.

01:05:49.050 --> 01:05:52.140
And that's not because
we're afraid of code,

01:05:52.140 --> 01:05:55.180
but because every line of
code you write is time.

01:05:55.180 --> 01:05:58.916
Every 10 lines of code
you write is a bug.

01:05:58.916 --> 01:06:00.374
[LAUGHTER]

01:06:00.374 --> 01:06:01.350
ANDREW GRANT: Right?

01:06:01.350 --> 01:06:03.205
So what we want to do
is minimize the number

01:06:03.205 --> 01:06:04.330
of lines of code you write.

01:06:04.330 --> 01:06:06.371
We want to minimize the
number of bugs you write.

01:06:06.371 --> 01:06:08.550
Because when it gets
to be the bug stage,

01:06:08.550 --> 01:06:11.050
that takes even more time--
to find it, to fix it,

01:06:11.050 --> 01:06:13.390
to write new code to fix it.

01:06:13.390 --> 01:06:16.340
So we want to reduce as much
as possible all of that time.

01:06:20.750 --> 01:06:23.700
So we want to use
all the tools we

01:06:23.700 --> 01:06:25.950
can to reduce the amount of
code we're going to write.

01:06:25.950 --> 01:06:29.030
One of our big ones is we use
what we call paper prototyping.

01:06:29.030 --> 01:06:30.270
We don't actually mean paper.

01:06:30.270 --> 01:06:33.680
We mean whatever materials
you can use-- chalk,

01:06:33.680 --> 01:06:35.920
pieces of plastic,
dice, frisbees.

01:06:35.920 --> 01:06:38.260
Anything you can use to make
your game without writing

01:06:38.260 --> 01:06:40.410
a line of code,
you should try it.

01:06:40.410 --> 01:06:41.140
Test it that way.

01:06:41.140 --> 01:06:44.030
Because it's so much
faster to test it that way.

01:06:44.030 --> 01:06:45.749
When else do we have up here?

01:06:45.749 --> 01:06:47.790
Iterative design-- I've
talked about this before.

01:06:47.790 --> 01:06:48.850
We're going to use
the phrase iterative

01:06:48.850 --> 01:06:51.760
design to talk about that whole
cycle where you try something,

01:06:51.760 --> 01:06:55.440
see how it worked or didn't
work, change it, try it again.

01:06:55.440 --> 01:06:56.230
That's iteration.

01:06:56.230 --> 01:06:59.237
And we're going to talk about
that a huge, huge amount.

01:06:59.237 --> 01:07:01.070
And one of the big parts
of this, of course,

01:07:01.070 --> 01:07:02.110
is game engines.

01:07:02.110 --> 01:07:03.770
Which is not to say
that you're going

01:07:03.770 --> 01:07:05.760
to build your game engine.

01:07:05.760 --> 01:07:07.690
But rather, you're
going to try stuff.

01:07:07.690 --> 01:07:09.940
And the game engines will
let you iterate faster,

01:07:09.940 --> 01:07:12.580
do more with less code,
and get more done.

01:07:16.560 --> 01:07:17.060
All right.

01:07:17.060 --> 01:07:18.410
So again, you're going
to use a game engine

01:07:18.410 --> 01:07:19.534
to save yourself some time.

01:07:19.534 --> 01:07:21.332
You don't want to
reinvent the wheel.

01:07:21.332 --> 01:07:23.040
I'm confident that
you could write a game

01:07:23.040 --> 01:07:25.060
engine if you wanted to.

01:07:25.060 --> 01:07:26.760
But I don't think
it's worth your time.

01:07:26.760 --> 01:07:28.472
Someone else has
already done it.

01:07:28.472 --> 01:07:30.930
They may or may not have done
a better job than you can do.

01:07:30.930 --> 01:07:33.140
But you can bet that
the thing that you're

01:07:33.140 --> 01:07:34.590
going to get from
your game engine

01:07:34.590 --> 01:07:36.092
will be faster than if
you stopped and wrote it

01:07:36.092 --> 01:07:36.670
from scratch.

01:07:39.930 --> 01:07:41.415
And then finally,
the game engine

01:07:41.415 --> 01:07:43.790
that you write from scratch--
for every 10 lines of code,

01:07:43.790 --> 01:07:44.577
you've got a bug.

01:07:44.577 --> 01:07:45.660
I'm making that number up.

01:07:45.660 --> 01:07:48.660
But it sounds good.

01:07:48.660 --> 01:07:50.890
That means that a game
engine you write has bugs.

01:07:50.890 --> 01:07:51.800
Now I'm not going to
claim that the game

01:07:51.800 --> 01:07:54.154
engines that we're
going to suggest you use

01:07:54.154 --> 01:07:54.820
don't have bugs.

01:07:54.820 --> 01:07:56.330
They totally have bugs.

01:07:56.330 --> 01:07:59.650
But what we have is 10,000
monkeys on the internet,

01:07:59.650 --> 01:08:02.130
using that game engine,
reporting the bugs.

01:08:02.130 --> 01:08:04.680
And there have been a lot of
cycles of people fixing bugs.

01:08:04.680 --> 01:08:08.756
And so hopefully, the worst
ones are out of your way.

01:08:10.956 --> 01:08:12.830
The other thing you can
do with a game engine

01:08:12.830 --> 01:08:14.820
is you can use it
as you tinker toys,

01:08:14.820 --> 01:08:16.149
as we talked about before.

01:08:16.149 --> 01:08:18.311
Your game engine has a list
of things it does well.

01:08:18.311 --> 01:08:18.810
Great.

01:08:18.810 --> 01:08:21.069
Use those things as tools.

01:08:21.069 --> 01:08:22.060
Take advantage of that.

01:08:22.060 --> 01:08:23.890
Do everything you
can with those tools.

01:08:23.890 --> 01:08:27.300
And if it can't do
something, don't fight it.

01:08:27.300 --> 01:08:30.069
Don't say, game engine, darn
you, if only did this thing.

01:08:30.069 --> 01:08:34.369
Think, how can we change
our design to not need that?

01:08:34.369 --> 01:08:35.910
That's another
advantage you can use,

01:08:35.910 --> 01:08:37.034
another trick you can play.

01:08:37.034 --> 01:08:38.990
If you limit your
design, sometimes it

01:08:38.990 --> 01:08:40.500
increases your creativity.

01:08:40.500 --> 01:08:42.791
And it can actually help you
get your game done faster.

01:08:45.859 --> 01:08:49.189
So throughout this
class, I use this phrase.

01:08:49.189 --> 01:08:50.439
I'm not sure anyone else does.

01:08:50.439 --> 01:08:53.512
But I consider certain
things to be nooses.

01:08:53.512 --> 01:08:55.720
There are some things we
will tell you you cannot do,

01:08:55.720 --> 01:08:58.220
or that we tell you
not to do, flat out.

01:08:58.220 --> 01:09:00.870
And those things--
don't do them.

01:09:00.870 --> 01:09:01.370
OK?

01:09:01.370 --> 01:09:03.453
But there are some things
that we're going to say,

01:09:03.453 --> 01:09:05.060
we recommend that
you don't do that.

01:09:05.060 --> 01:09:09.910
Or, you know, no team has
tried that and succeeded yet.

01:09:09.910 --> 01:09:11.870
Those I consider nooses.

01:09:11.870 --> 01:09:13.510
You can try them.

01:09:13.510 --> 01:09:15.189
And you can put
your head in there

01:09:15.189 --> 01:09:17.109
and see how comfortable it is.

01:09:17.109 --> 01:09:18.738
But probably by the
end of the class,

01:09:18.738 --> 01:09:20.029
you'll say, wow, you know what?

01:09:20.029 --> 01:09:22.760
When you said not to do
multiplayer networked play,

01:09:22.760 --> 01:09:24.600
you were right.

01:09:24.600 --> 01:09:27.210
We have heard that every year.

01:09:27.210 --> 01:09:30.720
We will hear it this
year, I suspect.

01:09:30.720 --> 01:09:34.370
But again, we're not telling
you to never try crazy things.

01:09:34.370 --> 01:09:38.189
But merely be aware of
what the crazy things are.

01:09:38.189 --> 01:09:40.789
If we're suggesting that you
not try something, but not

01:09:40.789 --> 01:09:43.330
telling you you can't do it,
and we're looking kind of pained

01:09:43.330 --> 01:09:45.340
when we say it, be
aware that this is

01:09:45.340 --> 01:09:46.756
a huge risk for your project.

01:09:46.756 --> 01:09:49.130
Be aware that this is a place
where you should be putting

01:09:49.130 --> 01:09:52.210
a lot of early attention to make
sure that you have a back-up

01:09:52.210 --> 01:09:54.572
plan if it fails.

01:09:58.290 --> 01:09:58.850
All right.

01:09:58.850 --> 01:09:59.659
On we go.

01:09:59.659 --> 01:10:02.200
Now we're actually going to talk
a little bit about the thing

01:10:02.200 --> 01:10:03.660
we're supposed to talk about.

01:10:03.660 --> 01:10:05.720
Picking a game engine
is super important.

01:10:05.720 --> 01:10:08.060
Everything involved in
your game relies on it.

01:10:08.060 --> 01:10:12.660
But again, contradictorily,
don't worry about it.

01:10:12.660 --> 01:10:14.660
Because you have four projects.

01:10:14.660 --> 01:10:17.055
And the first one doesn't
count for game engines,

01:10:17.055 --> 01:10:18.680
because you're not
using a game engine.

01:10:18.680 --> 01:10:20.710
But for two and three,
I'd say experiment.

01:10:20.710 --> 01:10:21.920
Try some stuff out.

01:10:21.920 --> 01:10:23.425
By the time you
hit project four,

01:10:23.425 --> 01:10:25.300
you should have some
opinions about what game

01:10:25.300 --> 01:10:27.580
engine works well for you.

01:10:27.580 --> 01:10:28.745
And try to get there.

01:10:28.745 --> 01:10:30.870
Try to use the one you're
comfortable with by then.

01:10:30.870 --> 01:10:34.729
But experiment on the first two.

01:10:34.729 --> 01:10:36.270
No game engine's
going to be perfect.

01:10:36.270 --> 01:10:37.130
They all have flaws.

01:10:37.130 --> 01:10:38.330
They all have advantages.

01:10:38.330 --> 01:10:40.282
And your job is to
find the game engine

01:10:40.282 --> 01:10:42.490
whose advantages you like
and whose disadvantages you

01:10:42.490 --> 01:10:44.860
can live with.

01:10:44.860 --> 01:10:48.570
And that will be different
for different people.

01:10:48.570 --> 01:10:49.070
All right.

01:10:49.070 --> 01:10:49.730
Here we go.

01:10:49.730 --> 01:10:50.830
So the most important
things we're

01:10:50.830 --> 01:10:52.100
talking about for
game engines-- this

01:10:52.100 --> 01:10:53.120
is not an issue for this class.

01:10:53.120 --> 01:10:54.910
We're only recommending
free game engines.

01:10:54.910 --> 01:10:56.920
But in general, if you're
trying to pick a game

01:10:56.920 --> 01:10:59.330
engine or a software of
any kind to help you,

01:10:59.330 --> 01:11:01.420
these are the three
categories of cost.

01:11:01.420 --> 01:11:04.960
I call things free if you
don't care about the cost.

01:11:04.960 --> 01:11:08.140
If it's $20, it's
practically free.

01:11:08.140 --> 01:11:11.680
But if it's $1,000 and
you're a college student,

01:11:11.680 --> 01:11:12.400
that's not free.

01:11:12.400 --> 01:11:13.490
That's painful.

01:11:13.490 --> 01:11:16.160
And if you're corporation,
however, $1,000 is free.

01:11:16.160 --> 01:11:17.960
So these categories change.

01:11:17.960 --> 01:11:20.670
For us, we're
talking about free.

01:11:20.670 --> 01:11:24.115
Impossible is CryENGINE
or something brutal

01:11:24.115 --> 01:11:26.340
where you get the source
license and do everything.

01:11:26.340 --> 01:11:28.160
But we're not going to do that.

01:11:28.160 --> 01:11:30.118
So this is the first one
that actually matters.

01:11:30.118 --> 01:11:31.840
It's does your game
have requirements

01:11:31.840 --> 01:11:33.644
that the game
engine has to meet?

01:11:33.644 --> 01:11:36.060
And for most part, in this
class, this also won't be true.

01:11:36.060 --> 01:11:39.272
Because you can choose your
requirements based on the game

01:11:39.272 --> 01:11:40.230
engine you're choosing.

01:11:40.230 --> 01:11:41.771
And our games are
pretty small scope.

01:11:41.771 --> 01:11:44.360
But basically, if you
need a special input,

01:11:44.360 --> 01:11:47.140
if you want to
publish to iOS, if you

01:11:47.140 --> 01:11:53.630
need to support network play--
which you don't, remember--

01:11:53.630 --> 01:11:56.700
then that might affect which
game engine you choose.

01:12:01.260 --> 01:12:04.310
This one is actually my
biggest important thing.

01:12:04.310 --> 01:12:06.270
Whatever you choose
for your game engine--

01:12:06.270 --> 01:12:07.810
and we're actually going
to give you a short list.

01:12:07.810 --> 01:12:09.610
So it's not quite
the open free-for-all

01:12:09.610 --> 01:12:11.250
you might be worried about.

01:12:11.250 --> 01:12:13.160
It should be easy to learn.

01:12:13.160 --> 01:12:14.920
And there's a couple
reasons for that.

01:12:14.920 --> 01:12:17.964
But the main reason is simply
the amount of time you've got.

01:12:17.964 --> 01:12:19.130
We don't have a lot of time.

01:12:19.130 --> 01:12:21.590
You don't want to spend time
mastering a game engine.

01:12:21.590 --> 01:12:24.270
You want to spend time mastering
the art of creating games.

01:12:24.270 --> 01:12:26.492
So you want to pick something
that's well-documented,

01:12:26.492 --> 01:12:28.200
that's got a good
online community that's

01:12:28.200 --> 01:12:29.670
going to help you out.

01:12:29.670 --> 01:12:31.170
Even if you don't
ask the questions,

01:12:31.170 --> 01:12:32.770
in a big enough
online community,

01:12:32.770 --> 01:12:34.750
someone's already asked
the question you have.

01:12:34.750 --> 01:12:36.130
I suspect you're all
familiar with this point.

01:12:36.130 --> 01:12:38.650
We can do a search for the
question you have on something.

01:12:38.650 --> 01:12:40.880
And some forum post pops up
where someone else has already

01:12:40.880 --> 01:12:42.050
asked the question you have.

01:12:42.050 --> 01:12:43.660
And you just read the
answers and think, yay!

01:12:43.660 --> 01:12:44.493
There was an answer.

01:12:44.493 --> 01:12:46.080
Or probably, there
wasn't an answer.

01:12:46.080 --> 01:12:47.592
I'll look at a
couple more of those.

01:12:47.592 --> 01:12:49.550
And so you can get an
idea for your game engine

01:12:49.550 --> 01:12:52.810
as to how robust the community
is, how good the support is,

01:12:52.810 --> 01:12:55.050
by sort of looking and
seeing how much support there

01:12:55.050 --> 01:12:55.980
is online for it.

01:12:58.580 --> 01:13:01.500
One thing on in-house experts--
it's very common for a team

01:13:01.500 --> 01:13:03.420
to come together and
say, well, we all

01:13:03.420 --> 01:13:05.580
know this game
engine a little bit.

01:13:05.580 --> 01:13:07.430
But there's this one
person on our team

01:13:07.430 --> 01:13:09.637
who's just an expert
in this other one.

01:13:09.637 --> 01:13:11.970
So we're going to rely on
that person to really teach us

01:13:11.970 --> 01:13:12.840
how to do it.

01:13:12.840 --> 01:13:15.620
That only, only works if
that person is really willing

01:13:15.620 --> 01:13:16.590
to be a teacher.

01:13:16.590 --> 01:13:19.670
And it's not a bad
thing if they're not.

01:13:19.670 --> 01:13:22.440
But don't choose their engine
based on their expertise

01:13:22.440 --> 01:13:24.360
if they're not willing
to really be a teacher.

01:13:24.360 --> 01:13:26.740
And what I mean by that
is that that person will

01:13:26.740 --> 01:13:30.405
have to be willing to not
write code a lot of the time.

01:13:30.405 --> 01:13:32.780
Because their time is better
spent teaching everyone else

01:13:32.780 --> 01:13:34.810
how to write code.

01:13:34.810 --> 01:13:36.900
And that really means
that if you find yourself

01:13:36.900 --> 01:13:38.316
in that situation,
where you think

01:13:38.316 --> 01:13:40.380
that you are the expert
in a particular engine,

01:13:40.380 --> 01:13:42.254
and you're trying to
get your team to use it,

01:13:42.254 --> 01:13:45.640
really think about yourself and
how you're feeling about that.

01:13:45.640 --> 01:13:48.270
Make sure that you are willing
to not dive in and write

01:13:48.270 --> 01:13:48.770
the code.

01:13:48.770 --> 01:13:50.894
Make sure that you're
willing to help everyone else

01:13:50.894 --> 01:13:51.990
do it instead.

01:13:51.990 --> 01:13:54.630
Because that is going to
leverage more of your team.

01:13:54.630 --> 01:13:56.960
On a small enough
team, that's not true.

01:13:56.960 --> 01:13:59.419
So on your two- or
three-person team,

01:13:59.419 --> 01:14:01.210
you can probably get
away with that expert.

01:14:01.210 --> 01:14:02.950
On an eight-person
team where five of you

01:14:02.950 --> 01:14:06.330
are coding something, you really
can't lean on that one person

01:14:06.330 --> 01:14:06.890
that heavily.

01:14:06.890 --> 01:14:08.306
You're going to
need to spread out

01:14:08.306 --> 01:14:09.950
the knowledge as best you can.

01:14:13.180 --> 01:14:16.006
And so some game engines are
easier to learn than others.

01:14:16.006 --> 01:14:17.880
It's not just a matter
of the online support.

01:14:20.450 --> 01:14:23.390
But we'll get to
that in a little bit.

01:14:23.390 --> 01:14:25.850
On a team programming
project-- and this

01:14:25.850 --> 01:14:27.277
is a personal bias of mine.

01:14:27.277 --> 01:14:28.860
And I admit that
some people disagree.

01:14:28.860 --> 01:14:32.110
But I personally think that
a strongly typed programming

01:14:32.110 --> 01:14:34.460
language is a must.

01:14:34.460 --> 01:14:39.310
If you're talking about
five to eight programmers,

01:14:39.310 --> 01:14:41.170
there's an additional problem.

01:14:41.170 --> 01:14:42.882
Whenever I write a
function, and you're

01:14:42.882 --> 01:14:44.340
going to call my
function, you have

01:14:44.340 --> 01:14:46.610
to know what the arguments are
to know what's going to happen.

01:14:46.610 --> 01:14:48.830
And a strongly typed language
will enforce that contract.

01:14:48.830 --> 01:14:51.121
It will make sure that we're
on the same page, at least

01:14:51.121 --> 01:14:53.960
a little bit, as to what
that function is doing.

01:14:53.960 --> 01:14:56.040
A lot of you are probably
used to-- MIT teaches,

01:14:56.040 --> 01:14:57.540
in a lot of the
programming classes,

01:14:57.540 --> 01:14:59.970
it uses Python, which is
awesome for quick work.

01:14:59.970 --> 01:15:02.410
And it's awesome for a
single person doing work.

01:15:02.410 --> 01:15:04.190
But it does kind of
start to fall apart

01:15:04.190 --> 01:15:07.080
on a larger team, when you have
to read someone else's code

01:15:07.080 --> 01:15:08.800
to know what their
function is doing,

01:15:08.800 --> 01:15:11.870
what the arguments
are supposed to be.

01:15:11.870 --> 01:15:14.680
If instead, you have a strongly
typed from the beginning,

01:15:14.680 --> 01:15:17.780
the compiler will enforce
this communication.

01:15:17.780 --> 01:15:20.880
And we're going to talk a lot
about teams and communication.

01:15:20.880 --> 01:15:23.690
It turns out your code is one of
your methods of communication.

01:15:23.690 --> 01:15:26.770
The actual written
text in your code

01:15:26.770 --> 01:15:28.554
is a way you talk to
your team members.

01:15:28.554 --> 01:15:29.970
And a strongly
typed language sort

01:15:29.970 --> 01:15:33.740
of forces you to keep that
communication line clearer

01:15:33.740 --> 01:15:37.740
than a weakly typed
language will.

01:15:37.740 --> 01:15:40.250
And again, this is one
of those things where

01:15:40.250 --> 01:15:43.080
programmers might have battles
over whether or not it's true.

01:15:43.080 --> 01:15:44.780
But I'm pretty
confident of this one.

01:15:44.780 --> 01:15:47.113
I would say it's a noose to
use a weakly typed language.

01:15:50.740 --> 01:15:54.140
A lot of our game engines are
going to be talking about C#,

01:15:54.140 --> 01:15:56.760
or ActionScript or whatever.

01:15:56.760 --> 01:15:59.895
And I'm going to tell you
that if you know one of those

01:15:59.895 --> 01:16:02.020
languages-- if you already
know Java, for example--

01:16:02.020 --> 01:16:04.160
it's really easy to
transition to C#.

01:16:04.160 --> 01:16:07.100
It's pretty easy to
transition to ActionScript.

01:16:07.100 --> 01:16:10.400
ActionScript and Haxe
are very similar.

01:16:10.400 --> 01:16:12.470
So I would say any
of those top four,

01:16:12.470 --> 01:16:15.320
you can transfer back
and fourth pretty easily.

01:16:15.320 --> 01:16:17.390
JavaScript, kind of.

01:16:17.390 --> 01:16:21.980
But don't try to transition
to C++ from those quickly.

01:16:21.980 --> 01:16:25.140
I mean obviously, you should
someday learn C++ if you are

01:16:25.140 --> 01:16:27.480
considering yourself a
Course 6 major or whatever.

01:16:27.480 --> 01:16:31.035
But don't assume you could pick
up C++ in a weekend because you

01:16:31.035 --> 01:16:33.130
already know Java.

01:16:33.130 --> 01:16:37.940
They're just gotchas in C++ that
don't exist in those languages.

01:16:37.940 --> 01:16:40.370
And other important
note, if you know Java--

01:16:40.370 --> 01:16:42.972
[LAUGHTER]

01:16:42.972 --> 01:16:45.263
ANDREW GRANT: It really looks
like you know JavaScript.

01:16:48.440 --> 01:16:49.390
And you kinda do.

01:16:49.390 --> 01:16:50.880
But you don't.

01:16:50.880 --> 01:16:53.740
And that's not to say that you
shouldn't make that transition.

01:16:53.740 --> 01:16:56.073
But be aware that it's going
to take a little bit longer

01:16:56.073 --> 01:16:57.032
than you think.

01:16:57.032 --> 01:16:58.490
There's a lot of
synthetic sharing.

01:16:58.490 --> 01:17:00.740
But JavaScript is a
weakly typed language

01:17:00.740 --> 01:17:03.330
that has a lot of weird,
very web-specific features.

01:17:03.330 --> 01:17:06.255
And just be aware that that's
not as easy a transition.

01:17:09.280 --> 01:17:14.149
I talked about ease of
understanding and learning.

01:17:14.149 --> 01:17:16.190
Actually using the engine
is also very important.

01:17:16.190 --> 01:17:18.570
How are you going to
get stuff done in it?

01:17:18.570 --> 01:17:22.142
If the engine has an interactive
debugger, that is wonderful.

01:17:22.142 --> 01:17:23.850
If it doesn't, then
you're relying mostly

01:17:23.850 --> 01:17:25.190
on print statements.

01:17:25.190 --> 01:17:26.940
And that's hard.

01:17:26.940 --> 01:17:29.840
If you've never really had the
joy of using a debugger before,

01:17:29.840 --> 01:17:31.210
I recommend you try to learn.

01:17:31.210 --> 01:17:33.730
Because it's really an
extremely powerful tool.

01:17:33.730 --> 01:17:36.322
We're not going to get into
that in detail right now.

01:17:36.322 --> 01:17:38.530
And source-control-friendly
is another important one.

01:17:38.530 --> 01:17:40.113
If you're on a team
with eight people,

01:17:40.113 --> 01:17:41.700
you're all going to
be making changes.

01:17:41.700 --> 01:17:43.650
We're going to talk more about
source control in the future.

01:17:43.650 --> 01:17:45.370
We're not going to go
into details on that now.

01:17:45.370 --> 01:17:46.700
But basically, it's
a way for your team

01:17:46.700 --> 01:17:48.824
the team to communicate
and make sure you're always

01:17:48.824 --> 01:17:51.340
in the same, up-to-date
source code for your project.

01:17:51.340 --> 01:17:53.380
And if your engine
doesn't support that,

01:17:53.380 --> 01:17:55.130
then you can be in trouble.

01:17:55.130 --> 01:17:57.600
In the past, for
example, people have

01:17:57.600 --> 01:18:00.300
talked about some of the cool,
sort of hobbyist game engines,

01:18:00.300 --> 01:18:04.330
like GameMaker, or back in
the day, just bare Flash.

01:18:04.330 --> 01:18:06.297
And those are really cool tools.

01:18:06.297 --> 01:18:07.880
But they would save
the entire project

01:18:07.880 --> 01:18:10.430
as one monolithic binary file.

01:18:10.430 --> 01:18:13.016
And so if one person
makes a change,

01:18:13.016 --> 01:18:15.390
no one else can change the
code while they're doing that.

01:18:15.390 --> 01:18:18.370
Because there's no way
to merge our changes.

01:18:18.370 --> 01:18:21.390
Whereas with code or text
files, or a good game engine

01:18:21.390 --> 01:18:23.020
that separates things
out a little bit,

01:18:23.020 --> 01:18:24.440
one person can
change an art asset

01:18:24.440 --> 01:18:26.130
while someone changes a code
file, while someone else

01:18:26.130 --> 01:18:27.610
changes yet another code file.

01:18:27.610 --> 01:18:29.533
And it all merges together
pretty seamlessly.

01:18:29.533 --> 01:18:31.533
And that's what you're
looking for, if possible,

01:18:31.533 --> 01:18:32.300
on a team project.

01:18:35.281 --> 01:18:37.030
I talked about this
before, but you really

01:18:37.030 --> 01:18:39.170
want a product that's
been around a little bit.

01:18:39.170 --> 01:18:42.750
It's cool as a hobbyist
thing or a solo product

01:18:42.750 --> 01:18:44.530
to take on something
really brand new.

01:18:44.530 --> 01:18:46.206
But I think for a
class where you're

01:18:46.206 --> 01:18:48.080
trying to get stuff done
really, really fast,

01:18:48.080 --> 01:18:50.030
and you're working
with a team, you really

01:18:50.030 --> 01:18:54.249
don't want to go too far in the
direction of the new, latest,

01:18:54.249 --> 01:18:55.040
and greatest thing.

01:18:55.040 --> 01:18:56.330
Because you want to
have a game engine

01:18:56.330 --> 01:18:57.940
that people have
put some miles on.

01:18:57.940 --> 01:19:00.190
They've tested it and
shaken out some of the bugs

01:19:00.190 --> 01:19:01.090
before you get to it.

01:19:04.570 --> 01:19:05.884
All right.

01:19:05.884 --> 01:19:07.300
Those are things
that I consider--

01:19:07.300 --> 01:19:09.260
you've got to have
them for a game engine.

01:19:09.260 --> 01:19:12.607
Here's some stuff
that's kind of nice.

01:19:12.607 --> 01:19:14.690
Yeah, it's nice to be able
to easily import images

01:19:14.690 --> 01:19:16.810
and sounds and stuff like that.

01:19:16.810 --> 01:19:20.360
It's nice to be able to get
the source code to the engine.

01:19:20.360 --> 01:19:23.730
But it's not essential if
the engine's well documented.

01:19:23.730 --> 01:19:24.530
Let's see.

01:19:24.530 --> 01:19:26.150
It's nice if you have an
integrated development

01:19:26.150 --> 01:19:27.950
environment that can help
you with auto-completion

01:19:27.950 --> 01:19:29.866
of various functions and
really help you along

01:19:29.866 --> 01:19:30.850
with your development.

01:19:30.850 --> 01:19:33.660
Definitely nice,
but not necessary.

01:19:33.660 --> 01:19:36.400
And then finally, an
editor of some kind--

01:19:36.400 --> 01:19:38.410
if I want to lay out
my levels in some way,

01:19:38.410 --> 01:19:40.760
is there a graphical
editor for me to do that?

01:19:40.760 --> 01:19:41.677
That's certainly nice.

01:19:41.677 --> 01:19:44.051
And a profiler that would tell
me where my game is slow--

01:19:44.051 --> 01:19:45.040
that's also nice.

01:19:45.040 --> 01:19:47.738
But without these things,
you could probably get by.

01:19:51.129 --> 01:19:52.670
Bells and whistles--
this is actually

01:19:52.670 --> 01:19:57.080
relatively unimportant,
especially for a small project,

01:19:57.080 --> 01:19:59.630
prototype-style stuff that
we're going to be talking about.

01:19:59.630 --> 01:20:01.102
For the most part,
you don't need

01:20:01.102 --> 01:20:03.310
all the fancy stuff like
particle systems and shaders

01:20:03.310 --> 01:20:04.890
and physics and all that stuff.

01:20:04.890 --> 01:20:06.810
You might use physics
in this class.

01:20:06.810 --> 01:20:09.624
But be careful.

01:20:09.624 --> 01:20:10.790
So that's one of the things.

01:20:10.790 --> 01:20:12.664
You don't need that
stuff in your game engine

01:20:12.664 --> 01:20:15.680
for most small games, at least
in the scope of this class.

01:20:15.680 --> 01:20:17.180
These are things
that I really don't

01:20:17.180 --> 01:20:19.951
care about-- scripting languages
that your designer might use.

01:20:19.951 --> 01:20:22.450
Why is your designer not writing
code in your strongly typed

01:20:22.450 --> 01:20:23.040
language?

01:20:23.040 --> 01:20:25.070
I never understood that one.

01:20:25.070 --> 01:20:27.040
Some designers are
afraid of writing code.

01:20:27.040 --> 01:20:28.498
But hopefully in
this class, you're

01:20:28.498 --> 01:20:31.852
at least willing to
try writing some code.

01:20:31.852 --> 01:20:33.810
And then finally, just
because someone has made

01:20:33.810 --> 01:20:35.299
a beautiful game
in a game engine,

01:20:35.299 --> 01:20:36.840
that has no bearing
on whether or not

01:20:36.840 --> 01:20:40.180
your game will be beautiful
in that game engine.

01:20:40.180 --> 01:20:43.520
The vast majority of the time,
a game built in a game engine

01:20:43.520 --> 01:20:47.130
is beautiful because they
have a really good art team.

01:20:47.130 --> 01:20:49.810
And we don't have a
really good art team here.

01:20:49.810 --> 01:20:51.330
We don't have the
time to do that.

01:20:51.330 --> 01:20:53.038
And we don't have the
resources to do it.

01:20:53.038 --> 01:20:55.780
So you shouldn't
measure your game up

01:20:55.780 --> 01:20:57.664
against the beautiful AAA games.

01:20:57.664 --> 01:20:59.080
You should be
measuring your games

01:20:59.080 --> 01:21:01.330
up against some indie, quick,
prototype type of games.

01:21:04.200 --> 01:21:08.916
All right, so
Flixel is the thing

01:21:08.916 --> 01:21:10.790
we've been recommending
for many, many years.

01:21:10.790 --> 01:21:16.030
This is the game engine that
is easiest, has the quickest

01:21:16.030 --> 01:21:17.730
learning curve I've seen.

01:21:17.730 --> 01:21:19.010
It gets everything done.

01:21:19.010 --> 01:21:22.080
It's very quick
to learn, to use.

01:21:22.080 --> 01:21:23.820
And it runs on the web.

01:21:23.820 --> 01:21:24.360
Great.

01:21:24.360 --> 01:21:26.970
That's pretty good easy stuff.

01:21:26.970 --> 01:21:30.440
It was developed by Adam Atomic
for a game called Canabalt,

01:21:30.440 --> 01:21:33.800
that you can see up there.

01:21:33.800 --> 01:21:36.230
The game that, as far
as I know, sort of

01:21:36.230 --> 01:21:39.580
popularized the infinite
runner genre, which we've seen

01:21:39.580 --> 01:21:41.160
clone after clone
after clone of.

01:21:41.160 --> 01:21:43.035
But I believe this
is at least where

01:21:43.035 --> 01:21:44.300
it entered my consciousness.

01:21:44.300 --> 01:21:47.920
And therefore, it must be where
it came into the world, right?

01:21:47.920 --> 01:21:49.041
But anyway.

01:21:49.041 --> 01:21:51.290
The cool thing about it is
it's got a very, very, very

01:21:51.290 --> 01:21:55.120
simple object-oriented
state-based system.

01:21:55.120 --> 01:21:58.430
It's really, really good
for 2D sprite stuff.

01:21:58.430 --> 01:22:00.930
Last year, we had a bunch of
game engines for people to try.

01:22:00.930 --> 01:22:03.320
By the end, pretty much
everyone just used Flixel.

01:22:03.320 --> 01:22:05.170
Because it was easier to use.

01:22:05.170 --> 01:22:08.767
And this kind of
says it all to me.

01:22:08.767 --> 01:22:10.350
Even if you haven't
used ActionScript,

01:22:10.350 --> 01:22:13.820
the learning curve
on Flixel is awesome.

01:22:13.820 --> 01:22:15.890
You'll spend a day
or two staring at it.

01:22:15.890 --> 01:22:18.510
And then you'll know most of
everything there is to know.

01:22:18.510 --> 01:22:20.146
And you'll just be
able to do stuff.

01:22:20.146 --> 01:22:22.100
You won't be able
to do all the cool,

01:22:22.100 --> 01:22:24.160
awesome stuff other game
engines will let you do.

01:22:24.160 --> 01:22:26.480
But you'll be able to do
pretty much everything you'll

01:22:26.480 --> 01:22:28.840
need to do on the scale
and scope of games you're

01:22:28.840 --> 01:22:29.881
looking at in this class.

01:22:34.090 --> 01:22:35.570
Let's see.

01:22:35.570 --> 01:22:37.827
It doesn't so good at GUI.

01:22:37.827 --> 01:22:39.910
If you wanted a fancy GUI--
lists and lots of text

01:22:39.910 --> 01:22:41.540
and buttons and
sliders and stuff--

01:22:41.540 --> 01:22:45.530
it's kind of a pain
to code that up.

01:22:45.530 --> 01:22:46.370
Right.

01:22:46.370 --> 01:22:50.110
So Flixel is also unfortunately,
in its current form, kind

01:22:50.110 --> 01:22:51.300
of in an end of life cycle.

01:22:51.300 --> 01:22:53.060
And I've been saying that
for two or three years now.

01:22:53.060 --> 01:22:54.280
And it's still holding on.

01:22:54.280 --> 01:22:56.610
Because Flash is
still holding on.

01:22:56.610 --> 01:22:58.370
Adobe is trying
to sort of get out

01:22:58.370 --> 01:23:00.760
of the business of maintaining
Flash as a web development

01:23:00.760 --> 01:23:02.370
place.

01:23:02.370 --> 01:23:03.657
And I'm not really sure why.

01:23:03.657 --> 01:23:05.240
Apparently, Adobe
decided a while back

01:23:05.240 --> 01:23:08.060
that HTML5 was the future.

01:23:08.060 --> 01:23:09.730
But it's been four
or five years now,

01:23:09.730 --> 01:23:12.790
and HTML5 is still
not the future.

01:23:12.790 --> 01:23:14.570
In the meantime, we're
sort of hanging on

01:23:14.570 --> 01:23:17.605
with Flash and the occasional
JavaScript HTML5 thing.

01:23:17.605 --> 01:23:19.730
I suspect it was actually
more of a financial thing

01:23:19.730 --> 01:23:22.080
than any actual HTML5
preference thing.

01:23:22.080 --> 01:23:23.960
But anyway, we're trying
to get out of Flixel

01:23:23.960 --> 01:23:27.390
a little bit in the long term,
because Flash is going to be

01:23:27.390 --> 01:23:28.961
a dying platform pretty soon.

