01:24:09.060 --> 01:24:11.440
I like writing code in it.

01:24:11.440 --> 01:24:14.050
But as soon as that
30-day free trial is over,

01:24:14.050 --> 01:24:16.990
you are on an annual
subscription paying Adobe money

01:24:16.990 --> 01:24:18.380
every year.

01:24:18.380 --> 01:24:20.990
So "free" with an asterisk.

01:24:20.990 --> 01:24:26.280
If you want to do free
development on a Mac

01:24:26.280 --> 01:24:30.550
and use Flixel, be
very, very careful.

01:24:30.550 --> 01:24:34.276
And use this upcoming
exercise to actually ensure

01:24:34.276 --> 01:24:35.900
that the things that
you're downloading

01:24:35.900 --> 01:24:37.608
and the things that
you're signing up for

01:24:37.608 --> 01:24:41.680
are actually free, and not
free for the first 30 days.

01:24:41.680 --> 01:24:44.470
For PC users, you have
the advantage of using

01:24:44.470 --> 01:24:46.310
FlashDevelop, I believe.

01:24:46.310 --> 01:24:48.494
That's what it's called.

01:24:48.494 --> 01:24:50.620
That is actually a
tool that you get

01:24:50.620 --> 01:24:52.466
without having to pay for it.

01:24:52.466 --> 01:24:54.590
For Linux, you are
pretty much stuck

01:24:54.590 --> 01:24:56.640
to using command-line compilers.

01:24:56.640 --> 01:25:00.240
And if you really want to do
free development on a Mac,

01:25:00.240 --> 01:25:01.990
you're also using
command-line But there's

01:25:01.990 --> 01:25:04.500
all kinds of clever things that
you can do with text editors

01:25:04.500 --> 01:25:07.440
to sort of make that a
little bit more comfortable.

01:25:07.440 --> 01:25:08.760
But just keep that in mind.

01:25:08.760 --> 01:25:10.700
That's another reason
why Flixel isn't

01:25:10.700 --> 01:25:14.130
our number one choice, nowadays,
is because Adobe's really

01:25:14.130 --> 01:25:17.450
trying to squeeze money out of
everybody, including students.

01:25:17.450 --> 01:25:19.247
Adobe's insane.

01:25:19.247 --> 01:25:20.663
ANDREW GRANT: One
can't blame them

01:25:20.663 --> 01:25:21.520
for trying to make a
little bit of money.

01:25:21.520 --> 01:25:23.811
However, it's no longer as
attractive as it used to be.

01:25:23.811 --> 01:25:26.150
That's certainly true.

01:25:26.150 --> 01:25:27.740
Unity is the next
one on our list

01:25:27.740 --> 01:25:29.260
that we've had
good success with.

01:25:32.945 --> 01:25:34.570
It's a free,
full-featured game engine.

01:25:34.570 --> 01:25:36.977
It's got all the bells and
whistles you could want.

01:25:36.977 --> 01:25:38.560
It's a little bit
dangerous to use it,

01:25:38.560 --> 01:25:40.690
because it has all the bells
and whistles you could want.

01:25:40.690 --> 01:25:42.400
And you should probably
only use some bells, and not

01:25:42.400 --> 01:25:43.890
the whistles, and whatever.

01:25:43.890 --> 01:25:45.680
You should be very
careful and judicious

01:25:45.680 --> 01:25:47.050
in your use of the features.

01:25:47.050 --> 01:25:49.216
Because the tinker
toy model of, only

01:25:49.216 --> 01:25:51.590
do what the engine lets you
do is a little bit dangerous.

01:25:51.590 --> 01:25:53.630
Because it lets you do
pretty much everything.

01:25:53.630 --> 01:25:55.379
So you have to be very
careful about which

01:25:55.379 --> 01:25:57.550
features you choose to use.

01:25:57.550 --> 01:25:59.020
However, it's great.

01:25:59.020 --> 01:25:59.570
It's free.

01:25:59.570 --> 01:26:02.140
It does a whole
bunch of neat stuff.

01:26:02.140 --> 01:26:04.620
There are paid versions.

01:26:04.620 --> 01:26:07.480
But you won't need them
for the class, certainly.

01:26:07.480 --> 01:26:09.150
I call these disads.

01:26:09.150 --> 01:26:11.770
3D is harder than 2D.

01:26:11.770 --> 01:26:14.980
And 3D is at least three
times as hard as 2D, really.

01:26:14.980 --> 01:26:16.170
It's rough.

01:26:16.170 --> 01:26:17.690
If you've never
done 3D before, it

01:26:17.690 --> 01:26:19.914
takes a while to get
your head into it.

01:26:19.914 --> 01:26:21.580
Even if you're doing
a 2D game in Unity,

01:26:21.580 --> 01:26:24.038
sometimes you have to think in
3D a little bit, which makes

01:26:24.038 --> 01:26:25.660
it a little bit harder to use.

01:26:25.660 --> 01:26:28.790
On the other hand, Unity
does have this nice editor.

01:26:28.790 --> 01:26:30.630
And it's possible
for a non-programmer

01:26:30.630 --> 01:26:32.690
to get some stuff done
in Unity in a way that's

01:26:32.690 --> 01:26:33.940
not possible in others.

01:26:33.940 --> 01:26:35.090
You spend more time
learning the GUI.

01:26:35.090 --> 01:26:37.048
But you can actually get
some more things done.

01:26:37.048 --> 01:26:40.430
So it's an interesting
little trade-off there.

01:26:40.430 --> 01:26:43.950
It is also, again,
not good at GUI work.

01:26:43.950 --> 01:26:46.140
They're starting to
address that a little bit.

01:26:46.140 --> 01:26:47.290
But it's hard.

01:26:47.290 --> 01:26:49.581
You have to kind of hand code
your buttons a little bit

01:26:49.581 --> 01:26:50.160
sometimes.

01:26:50.160 --> 01:26:51.390
That is improving, as I say.

01:26:51.390 --> 01:26:54.350
But it's not quite there yet.

01:26:54.350 --> 01:26:56.870
It suffers a little bit
from the problem of merging.

01:26:56.870 --> 01:26:59.490
Unity uses particular
objects that you really

01:26:59.490 --> 01:27:02.540
wish you could merge-- just so
they're text files or code--

01:27:02.540 --> 01:27:05.290
but you have a whole scene
of objects, for example.

01:27:05.290 --> 01:27:07.775
And only one person can
really work with it at a time,

01:27:07.775 --> 01:27:09.200
unless you're
really very careful.

01:27:09.200 --> 01:27:10.466
So when you're using
Unity, you have

01:27:10.466 --> 01:27:11.910
to be extra careful
with your team

01:27:11.910 --> 01:27:13.630
to make sure that
people aren't messing

01:27:13.630 --> 01:27:15.300
with the same files
at the same time.

01:27:15.300 --> 01:27:17.465
The code, however, works
the way you want it to.

01:27:17.465 --> 01:27:18.970
And source control works fine.

01:27:18.970 --> 01:27:20.470
So you've got to be careful.

01:27:20.470 --> 01:27:21.981
But you can work around it.

