01:29:38.290 --> 01:29:40.810
So when you're
learning an engine,

01:29:40.810 --> 01:29:41.930
you start with tutorials.

01:29:41.930 --> 01:29:43.530
That's the easiest thing to do.

01:29:43.530 --> 01:29:45.280
Once you've learned
three or four engines,

01:29:45.280 --> 01:29:46.530
you might not use tutorials.

01:29:46.530 --> 01:29:47.940
But until then, I would
say you should actually

01:29:47.940 --> 01:29:50.231
go through something that
someone's written and thought

01:29:50.231 --> 01:29:52.910
about how to progress.

01:29:52.910 --> 01:29:54.270
Do something extremely small.

01:29:54.270 --> 01:29:56.770
Don't start with the be-all and
end-all game of awesomeness.

01:29:56.770 --> 01:29:59.610
Start with something
very, very easy.

01:29:59.610 --> 01:30:01.310
And then after you've
done that, you're

01:30:01.310 --> 01:30:03.464
going to discover that
you've done some things.

01:30:03.464 --> 01:30:05.380
Then read the documentation
a little bit more.

01:30:05.380 --> 01:30:07.338
Because you're going to
be better at picking up

01:30:07.338 --> 01:30:09.300
stuff after you have
questions in your head.

01:30:09.300 --> 01:30:12.770
Even if you don't realize
what questions you've got.

01:30:12.770 --> 01:30:14.350
And we're warming
up to an assignment

01:30:14.350 --> 01:30:15.590
where we're going to
hand you a game engine

01:30:15.590 --> 01:30:17.881
and you're going to take a
look at it over the weekend,

01:30:17.881 --> 01:30:18.740
or over the week.

01:30:18.740 --> 01:30:20.260
But the thing you
need to remember

01:30:20.260 --> 01:30:24.550
is that all software
really does suck.

01:30:24.550 --> 01:30:26.125
And game engines
are no exception.

01:30:29.290 --> 01:30:31.733
At this point,
invariably, somebody

01:30:31.733 --> 01:30:35.370
will claim that
Linux doesn't suck.

01:30:35.370 --> 01:30:38.110
To which I'll have to
claim that it does.

01:30:38.110 --> 01:30:39.500
But it's also awesome.

01:30:39.500 --> 01:30:42.560
And that's the thing about
software and game engines.

01:30:42.560 --> 01:30:45.490
You have to really
understand and appreciate

01:30:45.490 --> 01:30:47.990
the ins and outs of Linux to
understand the ways in which it

01:30:47.990 --> 01:30:50.573
really does suck, but there are
ways in which it's really also

01:30:50.573 --> 01:30:52.520
really awesome.

01:30:52.520 --> 01:30:56.540
Operating systems all, really,
are pretty bad, I suspect.

01:30:56.540 --> 01:30:58.590
Windows and Mac-- you
can make huge arguments

01:30:58.590 --> 01:30:59.350
about all of them.

01:30:59.350 --> 01:31:00.766
Photoshop we talked
about earlier.

01:31:00.766 --> 01:31:02.360
It's an awesomely powerful tool.

01:31:02.360 --> 01:31:04.776
But to sit down and actually
start using it as a beginner,

01:31:04.776 --> 01:31:06.697
as a newbie, is a
miserable experience.

01:31:06.697 --> 01:31:09.030
I think you've probably all
had very similar experiences

01:31:09.030 --> 01:31:09.840
with software.

01:31:09.840 --> 01:31:10.540
It's buggy.

01:31:10.540 --> 01:31:12.040
It's painful.

01:31:12.040 --> 01:31:13.570
This is true for
game engines, too.

01:31:13.570 --> 01:31:14.840
You're going to try
out a game engine.

01:31:14.840 --> 01:31:16.290
And you're going to probably
come back to class thinking,

01:31:16.290 --> 01:31:17.000
I tried Unity.

01:31:17.000 --> 01:31:17.750
It was terrible.

01:31:17.750 --> 01:31:19.333
I didn't understand
what was going on.

01:31:19.333 --> 01:31:20.140
It was really hard.

01:31:20.140 --> 01:31:21.830
And then you'll hear someone
else talk about Flixel.

01:31:21.830 --> 01:31:24.288
And you'll think, wow, I didn't
have any of those problems.

01:31:24.288 --> 01:31:25.590
And so this is the trick.

01:31:25.590 --> 01:31:27.590
All software sucks.

01:31:27.590 --> 01:31:29.820
And your job is to find
the software that sucks

01:31:29.820 --> 01:31:32.820
in ways that you can handle.

01:31:32.820 --> 01:31:33.960
Right?

01:31:33.960 --> 01:31:35.800
You don't mind so
much that you have

01:31:35.800 --> 01:31:37.620
to think in 3D for
Unity, because you're

01:31:37.620 --> 01:31:39.810
willing to put up
with that because you

01:31:39.810 --> 01:31:42.490
get these cool,
nice, rendered look.

01:31:42.490 --> 01:31:44.200
Or maybe you have to
deal with the fact

01:31:44.200 --> 01:31:46.890
that, yeah, Flixel's
written in ActionScript 3.

01:31:46.890 --> 01:31:48.260
And ugh, I hate that language.

01:31:48.260 --> 01:31:50.120
But boy, it sure is easy to
put stuff up on the screen,

01:31:50.120 --> 01:31:51.869
and have spaceships
moving around shooting

01:31:51.869 --> 01:31:53.703
each other in, like, a
day, with no problem.

01:31:53.703 --> 01:31:55.535
And these are the kinds
of trade-offs you're

01:31:55.535 --> 01:31:56.754
going to have to look at.

01:31:56.754 --> 01:31:58.420
So when you're trying
to evaluate a game

01:31:58.420 --> 01:31:59.625
engine, or any piece
of software, really,

01:31:59.625 --> 01:32:01.292
but game engines for
this class, you're

01:32:01.292 --> 01:32:03.500
going to think about the
ways in which it's terrible.

01:32:03.500 --> 01:32:05.583
But also think about the
ways in which it's great.

01:32:05.583 --> 01:32:08.370
And when you get together and
talk with a team for projects

01:32:08.370 --> 01:32:11.480
two through four about
what game engine to use,

01:32:11.480 --> 01:32:13.860
you're going to want to be
able to say intelligently,

01:32:13.860 --> 01:32:16.700
I don't like Flixel
because of these things.

01:32:16.700 --> 01:32:18.880
But actually I can
live with those things.

01:32:18.880 --> 01:32:22.220
Or, I don't like Unity
because of this thing,

01:32:22.220 --> 01:32:23.877
and I really just
can't get past it.

01:32:23.877 --> 01:32:25.960
And if your team's insisting
on using that engine,

01:32:25.960 --> 01:32:28.170
and you really know you
really don't like it,

01:32:28.170 --> 01:32:29.860
consider another team.

01:32:29.860 --> 01:32:30.652
And that's not bad.

01:32:30.652 --> 01:32:32.985
Different people are going
to have different preferences

01:32:32.985 --> 01:32:33.910
for different styles.

01:32:33.910 --> 01:32:35.910
And that's part of what
we're going to be doing.

01:32:35.910 --> 01:32:37.010
Any time you're going
to be forming a team

01:32:37.010 --> 01:32:38.580
or trying to work
with a team, you're

01:32:38.580 --> 01:32:39.760
going to have to
figure out what works

01:32:39.760 --> 01:32:42.060
for you, what's hard for
you, what's easy for you.

01:32:42.060 --> 01:32:44.470
And match yourself up with
tasks or software that

01:32:44.470 --> 01:32:46.800
matches your set of skills.

01:32:46.800 --> 01:32:49.490
Or, if you want to
challenge yourself, OK.

01:32:49.490 --> 01:32:51.490
Be ready to challenge
yourself and try something

01:32:51.490 --> 01:32:53.540
that you thought was
too hard or too painful.

01:32:53.540 --> 01:32:54.820
But be aware that
you're doing that.

01:32:54.820 --> 01:32:56.100
Because you need to
let your team know,

01:32:56.100 --> 01:32:58.350
hey, I'm going to be on
a learning curve here.

01:32:58.350 --> 01:33:00.600
You're going to
have to help me out.

01:33:00.600 --> 01:33:02.920
So as you look at
a game engine, be

01:33:02.920 --> 01:33:05.340
aware that it is going
to disappoint you.

01:33:05.340 --> 01:33:06.770
That's just the way it is.

01:33:06.770 --> 01:33:10.890
But try to figure out where
the disappointments are.

