01:43:55.860 --> 01:43:58.080
So there's two types of
decision-making that I see.

01:43:58.080 --> 01:44:00.779
And again, this is all just
me in my head a couple days

01:44:00.779 --> 01:44:02.070
ago putting a lecture together.

01:44:02.070 --> 01:44:04.780
It's not an academic taxonomy.

01:44:04.780 --> 01:44:06.960
It's to help us out
when we're thinking

01:44:06.960 --> 01:44:09.540
about the kinds of decisions
we're making in these games.

01:44:09.540 --> 01:44:11.956
There's two kinds of decisions
that happen in these games.

01:44:11.956 --> 01:44:14.680
There's a micro-level
decision-- short-term decisions

01:44:14.680 --> 01:44:17.800
I make that help
me out right now.

01:44:17.800 --> 01:44:21.680
There's macro decisions
or long-term decisions.

01:44:21.680 --> 01:44:24.040
And I'm using micro
and macro because I'm

01:44:24.040 --> 01:44:26.620
obsessed with economics, even
though I don't understand it.

01:44:26.620 --> 01:44:29.780
But also because
you see the games

01:44:29.780 --> 01:44:31.120
represented that way sometimes.

01:44:31.120 --> 01:44:32.450
There's the micro,
where I'm looking really

01:44:32.450 --> 01:44:34.360
tight at this one
aspect of the game,

01:44:34.360 --> 01:44:37.820
and the macro, where
I can see a bigger,

01:44:37.820 --> 01:44:39.320
expanded version of the world.

01:44:39.320 --> 01:44:41.800
I can see the systems
and the gears that

01:44:41.800 --> 01:44:43.710
are happening behind the world.

01:44:43.710 --> 01:44:45.400
And they're represented
in many ways.

01:44:45.400 --> 01:44:47.284
And I'll talk about a
couple examples there.

01:44:47.284 --> 01:44:48.950
ANDREW GRANT: People
often use "tactics"

01:44:48.950 --> 01:44:53.087
to describe micro, and
"strategy" to describe macro.

01:44:53.087 --> 01:44:55.670
So there's actually a difference
between strategy and tactics.

01:44:55.670 --> 01:44:57.170
That's one way of
thinking about it.

01:44:57.170 --> 01:44:59.440
RIK EBERHARDT: Yeah.

01:44:59.440 --> 01:45:01.920
So for the micro--
exactly, tactical.

01:45:05.260 --> 01:45:07.214
The way this is
often represented

01:45:07.214 --> 01:45:09.130
in these kind of war
games or strategy games--

01:45:09.130 --> 01:45:11.463
there's usually some kind of
spatial component going on.

01:45:11.463 --> 01:45:13.484
There's some kind of
placement going on.

01:45:13.484 --> 01:45:15.400
There might be some
direct conflict happening.

01:45:15.400 --> 01:45:17.250
So I've got an army.

01:45:17.250 --> 01:45:18.800
And it's facing
off another army.

01:45:18.800 --> 01:45:21.820
And we're throwing spears
or shooting each other

01:45:21.820 --> 01:45:25.250
with lasers-- basically
the same thing.

01:45:25.250 --> 01:45:26.690
But there's also firefighting.

01:45:26.690 --> 01:45:28.010
There's another kind of
conflict that happens.

01:45:28.010 --> 01:45:29.676
And by firefighting,
I don't mean fires.

01:45:29.676 --> 01:45:32.745
But I've got a problem
that just happened.

01:45:32.745 --> 01:45:33.934
And I need to solve it.

01:45:33.934 --> 01:45:34.850
I need to react to it.

01:45:34.850 --> 01:45:37.530
So it's reactive.

01:45:37.530 --> 01:45:40.760
I might have this really
long long-term strategy.

01:45:40.760 --> 01:45:43.470
But unfortunately I've
got to make some decisions

01:45:43.470 --> 01:45:46.169
right now that may or may not
hurt my long-term strategy.

01:45:46.169 --> 01:45:48.210
There are some tactical
decisions I need to make.

01:45:50.775 --> 01:45:52.150
It's not always
reactive, though.

01:45:52.150 --> 01:45:53.450
Sometimes what
we're talking about

01:45:53.450 --> 01:45:54.630
is you're executing a plan.

01:45:54.630 --> 01:45:56.800
I've set up a
long-term strategy.

01:45:56.800 --> 01:45:58.680
And now here's the
final dramatic moment

01:45:58.680 --> 01:46:00.780
where I get to actually
implement the thing

01:46:00.780 --> 01:46:06.390
and see if it works--
throw the dudes on the map,

01:46:06.390 --> 01:46:09.467
and they're going to die or not.

01:46:09.467 --> 01:46:11.050
And when we're talking
about tactical,

01:46:11.050 --> 01:46:13.490
there's always a
short-term resolution.

01:46:13.490 --> 01:46:15.830
So I do a thing-- feedback.

01:46:15.830 --> 01:46:16.780
I know it happened.

01:46:16.780 --> 01:46:18.794
There could be
long-term ramifications.

01:46:18.794 --> 01:46:20.710
But there's definitely
a short-term resolution

01:46:20.710 --> 01:46:23.940
to the decision I just
made at that point.

01:46:23.940 --> 01:46:26.370
So my example, because
I am a huge Civilization

01:46:26.370 --> 01:46:31.760
nerd-- Civilization V brought
some very tactical game

01:46:31.760 --> 01:46:33.990
play to the series
that wasn't really

01:46:33.990 --> 01:46:37.140
there in previous installments.

01:46:37.140 --> 01:46:39.350
So in the past, you could
stack units on a tile.

01:46:39.350 --> 01:46:41.700
So Civilization is
basically a game

01:46:41.700 --> 01:46:44.870
made of tiles where you're
placing items on tiles.

01:46:44.870 --> 01:46:47.832
And the tiles give you
bonuses or whatnot.

01:46:47.832 --> 01:46:49.740
That's the very, very
basic version of it.

01:46:49.740 --> 01:46:51.990
In this case, what we have--
and it's kind of blurry--

01:46:51.990 --> 01:46:54.230
but you have a city
in the center, where

01:46:54.230 --> 01:46:56.020
that arrow is pointing to.

01:46:56.020 --> 01:46:58.940
You have these blue units
surrounding the city,

01:46:58.940 --> 01:47:01.900
and a couple small
yellow units going on.

01:47:01.900 --> 01:47:04.682
Can anybody describe what's
going on in this scene?

01:47:04.682 --> 01:47:05.390
AUDIENCE: A raid.

01:47:05.390 --> 01:47:05.860
RIK EBERHARDT: What's that?

01:47:05.860 --> 01:47:06.600
AUDIENCE: A raid.

01:47:06.600 --> 01:47:07.516
RIK EBERHARDT: A raid.

01:47:07.516 --> 01:47:09.130
So we're fighting.

01:47:09.130 --> 01:47:10.600
What kind of
decisions is a player

01:47:10.600 --> 01:47:13.280
being asked to do right now?

01:47:13.280 --> 01:47:15.090
And the player is
the blue player

01:47:15.090 --> 01:47:16.571
that has the red arrow there.

01:47:16.571 --> 01:47:18.680
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:47:18.680 --> 01:47:19.886
RIK EBERHARDT: What's that?

01:47:19.886 --> 01:47:20.760
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:47:20.760 --> 01:47:20.980
RIK EBERHARDT: So yeah.

01:47:20.980 --> 01:47:22.690
You're trying to
implement the strategy.

01:47:22.690 --> 01:47:24.898
Can you kind of see--
apologies if you can't make out

01:47:24.898 --> 01:47:28.770
the quality of the slide.

01:47:28.770 --> 01:47:33.280
Can you see what is
exactly going on?

01:47:33.280 --> 01:47:33.943
Yeah.

01:47:33.943 --> 01:47:36.568
AUDIENCE: They're about to make
a ranged attack with the cannon

01:47:36.568 --> 01:47:37.797
against the city.

01:47:37.797 --> 01:47:38.630
RIK EBERHARDT: Yeah.

01:47:38.630 --> 01:47:40.440
So first thing is,
all right, so I've

01:47:40.440 --> 01:47:45.140
got a range attack that
is really diagonally away

01:47:45.140 --> 01:47:46.400
from the city.

01:47:46.400 --> 01:47:47.940
It's two hexes away.

01:47:47.940 --> 01:47:49.190
I can do a range attack on it.

01:47:49.190 --> 01:47:51.330
The cool thing about
this is that the city

01:47:51.330 --> 01:47:53.240
can't attack me right now.

01:47:53.240 --> 01:47:54.510
Well, actually it can.

01:47:54.510 --> 01:47:57.169
But I'm making a mistake there.

01:47:57.169 --> 01:47:58.460
But it's not the knight's turn.

01:47:58.460 --> 01:48:01.210
So the knight can't attack
the ranged attack right now.

01:48:01.210 --> 01:48:03.219
The other thing that's
happening is the player

01:48:03.219 --> 01:48:05.510
had a long-term strategy,
which meant that they brought

01:48:05.510 --> 01:48:08.980
some foot soldiers in
to surround the city,

01:48:08.980 --> 01:48:11.900
protecting the ranged attacker.

01:48:11.900 --> 01:48:14.030
They've also got this thing
called Zone of Control

01:48:14.030 --> 01:48:14.800
going on in this.

01:48:19.728 --> 01:48:23.022
All right, here's
an enemy person.

01:48:23.022 --> 01:48:23.980
Here's an enemy person.

01:48:23.980 --> 01:48:25.390
Here's an enemy person.

01:48:25.390 --> 01:48:27.620
If any of these
people try to attack

01:48:27.620 --> 01:48:29.710
any of these blue
people, there's

01:48:29.710 --> 01:48:32.020
some kind of negative
modifier going on.

01:48:32.020 --> 01:48:35.430
Because the blue player
has set it up such that

01:48:35.430 --> 01:48:37.120
they're being flanked.

01:48:37.120 --> 01:48:38.930
So there's some
spatial placement

01:48:38.930 --> 01:48:41.080
going on that's been decided.

01:48:41.080 --> 01:48:43.370
Not only did they have to
get all the units over here,

01:48:43.370 --> 01:48:44.300
but once they were
here, they had

01:48:44.300 --> 01:48:46.200
to put those units
in the right places

01:48:46.200 --> 01:48:50.800
for this tactical
maneuver to happen.

01:48:53.350 --> 01:48:54.990
So really, in
Civilization V, we're

01:48:54.990 --> 01:48:57.420
talking about tactical
in one aspect of it.

01:48:57.420 --> 01:48:59.250
In the combat
aspect of it, we're

01:48:59.250 --> 01:49:03.590
talking about flanking, army
positioning, Zone of Control,

01:49:03.590 --> 01:49:06.970
preventing other players
from entering into tiles,

01:49:06.970 --> 01:49:10.920
controlling areas, and making
this area basically more

01:49:10.920 --> 01:49:13.320
effective for the
blue player to attack

01:49:13.320 --> 01:49:17.710
the city than for the
yellow player to defend it.

01:49:17.710 --> 01:49:19.640
So how did the player get there?

01:49:19.640 --> 01:49:22.800
How did blue get
into that situation?

01:49:22.800 --> 01:49:26.590
They had an operational
or strategic plan

01:49:26.590 --> 01:49:27.860
that they set forth.

01:49:27.860 --> 01:49:30.425
They were able to develop
those weapons that they had.

01:49:30.425 --> 01:49:33.250
They were able to make
them in the right location.

01:49:33.250 --> 01:49:36.030
And then they were able
to transport them over

01:49:36.030 --> 01:49:37.410
to the right location.

01:49:37.410 --> 01:49:42.500
So if we're talking
about military strategy,

01:49:42.500 --> 01:49:47.530
tactics, that might be
closer to logistics,

01:49:47.530 --> 01:49:51.515
supply chain, getting
supply into the area.

01:49:51.515 --> 01:49:53.390
The strategy that might
actually be happening

01:49:53.390 --> 01:49:55.050
is even bigger than that.

01:49:55.050 --> 01:49:57.670
So this is where it
gets into the realm

01:49:57.670 --> 01:50:00.230
that I really nerd
out in is spreadsheets

01:50:00.230 --> 01:50:02.400
of numbers and modifiers.

01:50:02.400 --> 01:50:05.900
There's resources
you need to manage.

01:50:05.900 --> 01:50:08.900
I need to anticipate what's
going to be there and have

01:50:08.900 --> 01:50:11.510
the right things
built in time for them

01:50:11.510 --> 01:50:14.450
to be useful in that situation.

01:50:14.450 --> 01:50:17.360
There's an economic system
I need to manipulate and do

01:50:17.360 --> 01:50:20.992
well with in order to afford the
units that I want over there.

01:50:20.992 --> 01:50:23.450
If I'm playing well, I need to
be proactive in my strategy.

01:50:23.450 --> 01:50:26.330
All strategy really
should be proactive.

01:50:26.330 --> 01:50:29.250
And someone can argue with
me if there is such a thing

01:50:29.250 --> 01:50:30.440
as reactive strategy.

01:50:30.440 --> 01:50:33.310
But really, it could
be proactive and wrong.

01:50:33.310 --> 01:50:35.390
But you did it beforehand.

01:50:35.390 --> 01:50:37.675
You set up the gears
in motion for it

01:50:37.675 --> 01:50:38.990
to play out the way it did.

01:50:38.990 --> 01:50:41.650
And you're always planning
for some long-term future.

01:50:41.650 --> 01:50:46.160
So in Civilization V, one way
that this plays out non-combat

01:50:46.160 --> 01:50:49.060
is city placement.

01:50:49.060 --> 01:50:52.040
Where I put my city is
incredibly important.

01:50:52.040 --> 01:50:56.770
Using the real world map of
Africa, what they've done

01:50:56.770 --> 01:50:59.960
is the designers put
these resources--

01:50:59.960 --> 01:51:07.225
those circular items-- spices,
bananas, silk, diamonds, oil.

01:51:07.225 --> 01:51:10.490
Some of the resources
are luxury resources.

01:51:10.490 --> 01:51:12.950
So they help my cities be happy.

01:51:12.950 --> 01:51:16.120
They help my citizens work
well and be productive.

01:51:16.120 --> 01:51:19.940
There's agricultural
resources that help

01:51:19.940 --> 01:51:22.090
my cities grow and be healthy.

01:51:22.090 --> 01:51:24.310
And then there's
strategic resources--

01:51:24.310 --> 01:51:25.900
and I could be mixing
these terms up.

01:51:25.900 --> 01:51:28.420
They're things that are going
to help me build things.

01:51:28.420 --> 01:51:33.840
So oil or steel or iron will
help me build better units.

01:51:33.840 --> 01:51:36.440
So my strategy here--
there's a little bit

01:51:36.440 --> 01:51:38.240
of tactics going on,
where when I actually

01:51:38.240 --> 01:51:39.680
get my settler in
the right place,

01:51:39.680 --> 01:51:43.185
I need to then find a
very specific place to go.

01:51:43.185 --> 01:51:45.310
But long-term, if I'm
thinking about the long term,

01:51:45.310 --> 01:51:47.310
I want to place
my cities in a way

01:51:47.310 --> 01:51:49.410
where they're near resources.

01:51:49.410 --> 01:51:51.020
They're near my friendly cities.

01:51:51.020 --> 01:51:51.979
They have room to grow.

01:51:51.979 --> 01:51:54.186
Because if I group my cities
too close to each other,

01:51:54.186 --> 01:51:55.790
they're not going
to be as efficient.

01:51:55.790 --> 01:51:57.570
This is really
apparent if anybody's

01:51:57.570 --> 01:52:00.760
