01:54:19.660 --> 01:54:23.570
But I just want to kind of
get these two terms out there.

01:54:23.570 --> 01:54:27.070
We're going to talk about
conflict and tension.

01:54:27.070 --> 01:54:32.470
So what is conflict?

01:54:32.470 --> 01:54:34.860
If I say the words
conflict and tension,

01:54:34.860 --> 01:54:38.070
what's the definitions
you're more familiar with?

01:54:41.010 --> 01:54:43.117
Anybody heard it in
drama or writing?

01:54:43.117 --> 01:54:44.950
Like the narrative arc--
there's a conflict.

01:54:44.950 --> 01:54:48.330
There are two people
who want the same thing.

01:54:48.330 --> 01:54:50.724
Or there's an internal conflict.

01:54:50.724 --> 01:54:52.682
And that's really what
I'm thinking of when I'm

01:54:52.682 --> 01:54:53.890
saying conflict in this case.

01:54:53.890 --> 01:54:56.910
It's, what is the conflict
in the player as they're

01:54:56.910 --> 01:54:58.460
making these decisions?

01:54:58.460 --> 01:55:00.960
What are the trade-offs
they're making?

01:55:00.960 --> 01:55:03.600
Do I send an army this way?

01:55:03.600 --> 01:55:05.200
Or do I send an army that way?

01:55:05.200 --> 01:55:07.340
Or do I not fight at all?

01:55:07.340 --> 01:55:09.720
If that is a really hard
decision for the player

01:55:09.720 --> 01:55:12.570
to make-- if they can't
calculate it beforehand,

01:55:12.570 --> 01:55:16.037
if they have enough information
to know that one may be better

01:55:16.037 --> 01:55:17.870
than the other, but
they're not quite sure--

01:55:17.870 --> 01:55:19.786
that's what we're talking
about with conflict.

01:55:19.786 --> 01:55:21.400
With what Pablo was
playing with us,

01:55:21.400 --> 01:55:24.877
the conflict in the
individual teams of,

01:55:24.877 --> 01:55:25.960
we know the probabilities.

01:55:25.960 --> 01:55:28.160
We can calculate that.

01:55:28.160 --> 01:55:29.707
But are we sure?

01:55:29.707 --> 01:55:31.540
Are we sure it's going
to play out that way?

01:55:31.540 --> 01:55:33.180
I really wish he
had used to cones.

01:55:33.180 --> 01:55:34.970
Because I really want
to know how often

01:55:34.970 --> 01:55:39.170
the cone's going
to fall on its end.

01:55:39.170 --> 01:55:42.062
And then tension are ways
we can modify that conflict.

01:55:42.062 --> 01:55:43.520
Maybe there's no
conflict existing.

01:55:43.520 --> 01:55:46.160
And we need to use tension
to create some conflict.

01:55:46.160 --> 01:55:48.390
Maybe there's a little
bit of conflict going on,

01:55:48.390 --> 01:55:51.730
and tension's going to amplify
that and make it more dramatic.

01:55:51.730 --> 01:55:54.470
And there's just some basic
things you can change.

01:55:54.470 --> 01:55:57.120
And when we talk about
the example games,

01:55:57.120 --> 01:55:59.500
and if you play these example
games over the weekend,

01:55:59.500 --> 01:56:02.030
think about these terms.

01:56:02.030 --> 01:56:04.230
If I were to change
the timing in a game,

01:56:04.230 --> 01:56:06.370
or the speed with which
you can make decisions,

01:56:06.370 --> 01:56:09.850
or the precision that's required
to make those decisions--

01:56:09.850 --> 01:56:11.340
would that increase
the conflict?

01:56:11.340 --> 01:56:13.790
And by increasing
the conflict there,

01:56:13.790 --> 01:56:15.300
are the choices
more interesting?

01:56:15.300 --> 01:56:18.500
Is the game more engaging,
or the game more fun?

01:56:18.500 --> 01:56:20.750
Limitations are
awesome in games.

01:56:20.750 --> 01:56:25.400
Limitations are really how you
can design and control where

01:56:25.400 --> 01:56:27.000
and what a player can do.

01:56:27.000 --> 01:56:29.380
So how many options do
you give the player?

01:56:29.380 --> 01:56:33.429
Do you give them two, or
three, or five, or infinite?

01:56:33.429 --> 01:56:34.470
I can tell you right now.

01:56:34.470 --> 01:56:36.650
Having infinite choices is
really, really difficult,

01:56:36.650 --> 01:56:38.340
but not that interesting.

01:56:38.340 --> 01:56:44.350
Space, costs, economics,
information, fog of war--

01:56:44.350 --> 01:56:46.390
we've seen in some of
these strategy games

01:56:46.390 --> 01:56:48.250
where you can only
see things that are

01:56:48.250 --> 01:56:49.250
around where your units.

01:56:49.250 --> 01:56:51.920
And you can't see
things outside of that.

01:56:51.920 --> 01:56:55.300
These are all methods we use as
designers to create conflict,

01:56:55.300 --> 01:56:57.467
to make those choices that
we're asking our players

01:56:57.467 --> 01:56:58.300
to make interesting.

