02:00:01.670 --> 02:00:03.497
Or if you get yourself
too tangled up,

02:00:03.497 --> 02:00:05.330
you can't move even
when you're by yourself.

02:00:05.330 --> 02:00:06.620
Have you done that or seen that?

02:00:06.620 --> 02:00:07.750
Someone's off by
themselves doing Twister

02:00:07.750 --> 02:00:09.590
and they fall over
with no one near them?

02:00:09.590 --> 02:00:11.634
It totally happens.

02:00:11.634 --> 02:00:13.550
There's other strategic
decisions for Twister.

02:00:13.550 --> 02:00:14.650
Are you trying to win?

02:00:14.650 --> 02:00:18.800
Are you trying to stay near
someone, or away from someone?

02:00:18.800 --> 02:00:21.780
There are totally other
game goals to Twister.

02:00:21.780 --> 02:00:25.590
And they're up to the
people who are playing it.

02:00:25.590 --> 02:00:26.791
What is next?

02:00:26.791 --> 02:00:27.624
RIK EBERHARDT: Sara.

02:00:27.624 --> 02:00:28.374
SARA VERRILLI: OK.

02:00:28.374 --> 02:00:30.516
That would be me.

02:00:30.516 --> 02:00:32.926
So this is not what
everybody thinks of when

02:00:32.926 --> 02:00:33.580
they think of strategic games.

02:00:33.580 --> 02:00:35.371
But I want to point
out that decisions come

02:00:35.371 --> 02:00:37.760
in a lot of different styles.

02:00:37.760 --> 02:00:40.900
You're not going to ever ruin
your game by any decisions

02:00:40.900 --> 02:00:42.399
you make in FarmVille,
particularly.

02:00:42.399 --> 02:00:44.169
But it is a game
that makes people

02:00:44.169 --> 02:00:45.710
make a lot of choices
about what they

02:00:45.710 --> 02:00:46.959
want to do, relatively freely.

02:00:49.740 --> 02:00:52.680
The strategy-- where strategy
and resource management

02:00:52.680 --> 02:00:55.680
comes into FarmVille is
you have a limited number

02:00:55.680 --> 02:00:56.680
of actions you can take.

02:00:56.680 --> 02:00:58.460
Which means you can only
play the game for so long.

02:00:58.460 --> 02:01:00.650
Assuming you do not want to
become one of those people who

02:01:00.650 --> 02:01:02.775
spends a big pile of money
playing FarmVille, which

02:01:02.775 --> 02:01:05.930
I'm going to assume you are.

02:01:05.930 --> 02:01:07.600
So you need to
manage your actions,

02:01:07.600 --> 02:01:09.110
and think about how many
actions you're taking,

02:01:09.110 --> 02:01:11.409
and think about when you want
to come back to the game.

02:01:11.409 --> 02:01:12.950
And the way they do
that, and the way

02:01:12.950 --> 02:01:14.360
that you can game
that system, is

02:01:14.360 --> 02:01:16.760
by looking at how long
it takes things to grow,

02:01:16.760 --> 02:01:18.760
what you want to grow,
what you want to make.

02:01:18.760 --> 02:01:20.968
FarmVille is actually at
this point kind of outdated,

02:01:20.968 --> 02:01:22.910
because they've
moved to FarmVille 2.

02:01:22.910 --> 02:01:25.140
But I did not actually
want to go there and play

02:01:25.140 --> 02:01:27.762
it to have the expertise
to tell you about it.

02:01:27.762 --> 02:01:29.470
I did spend enough
time playing FarmVille

02:01:29.470 --> 02:01:31.650
to know that there's
actually a whole lot

02:01:31.650 --> 02:01:33.755
of interesting decisions
you get to make there.

02:01:33.755 --> 02:01:35.630
And it's not a game
people think of when they

02:01:35.630 --> 02:01:36.610
think of meaningful decisions.

02:01:36.610 --> 02:01:38.151
Because they've
heard a whole lot of,

02:01:38.151 --> 02:01:41.340
oh my god, it's that click game.

02:01:41.340 --> 02:01:43.450
Just because it's
a game that doesn't

02:01:43.450 --> 02:01:46.480
have a lot of deep
consequences doesn't

02:01:46.480 --> 02:01:49.632
mean it can't have
a lot of deep play.

02:01:49.632 --> 02:01:51.340
Am I hitting the right button?

02:01:51.340 --> 02:01:52.730
Let's find out.

02:01:52.730 --> 02:01:56.630
So Plants vs. Zombies is
essentially a really popular

02:01:56.630 --> 02:01:57.510
tower defense game.

02:01:57.510 --> 02:01:59.140
And tower defense
was not very popular

02:01:59.140 --> 02:02:00.997
until Plants vs.
Zombies came out.

02:02:00.997 --> 02:02:02.830
Because most people
hadn't done it very well

02:02:02.830 --> 02:02:05.390
or presented it very well.

02:02:05.390 --> 02:02:09.060
But in Plants vs. Zombies,
you've got tons of choices.

02:02:09.060 --> 02:02:10.940
Who here has played
Plants vs. Zombies?

02:02:10.940 --> 02:02:11.910
Let me ask the first question.

02:02:11.910 --> 02:02:12.290
OK.

02:02:12.290 --> 02:02:13.998
So yeah, you know what
I'm talking about.

02:02:16.790 --> 02:02:18.500
They got the UI
right, absolutely.

02:02:18.500 --> 02:02:20.360
So it's easy to play.

02:02:20.360 --> 02:02:23.870
And every time you go in to
play a level, you get to choose.

02:02:23.870 --> 02:02:25.750
Which strategy are
you going to use?

02:02:25.750 --> 02:02:27.601
You've got sort of
the long-term strategy

02:02:27.601 --> 02:02:29.100
choice for each
level, where you get

02:02:29.100 --> 02:02:30.300
to choose which
creatures you're taking

02:02:30.300 --> 02:02:31.540
or which plants you're taking.

02:02:31.540 --> 02:02:32.920
And you can go back
and play each level

02:02:32.920 --> 02:02:34.770
with a completely
different set of plants,

02:02:34.770 --> 02:02:36.900
and still succeed,
or fail at it.

02:02:36.900 --> 02:02:40.280
In my case, it's
often more failing.

02:02:40.280 --> 02:02:41.830
They give you just
enough information

02:02:41.830 --> 02:02:43.913
so you can think about
what you're going to bring.

02:02:46.350 --> 02:02:47.970
You can see what's coming in.

02:02:47.970 --> 02:02:49.520
You don't know how many of
those are going to come.

02:02:49.520 --> 02:02:51.269
You don't know when
they're going to come.

02:02:51.269 --> 02:02:54.087
So you have to both
plan for, I know there's

02:02:54.087 --> 02:02:55.170
going to be a zombie need.

02:02:55.170 --> 02:02:56.530
But I don't know how
much of them it is.

02:02:56.530 --> 02:02:58.113
How much resources
do I need to devote

02:02:58.113 --> 02:03:03.810
to worrying about the
zom-- zom-- zombies.

02:03:03.810 --> 02:03:06.164
I'm not getting that
right at all, am I?

02:03:06.164 --> 02:03:08.330
How much resources do I
have to worry about devoting

02:03:08.330 --> 02:03:10.663
to that versus all the other
threats I've got coming in?

02:03:13.330 --> 02:03:16.114
Now I have to admit
something terrible.

02:03:16.114 --> 02:03:17.280
My daughters play this game.

02:03:17.280 --> 02:03:18.904
And I have watched
them play this game.

02:03:18.904 --> 02:03:20.640
But I haven't actually
played this game.

02:03:20.640 --> 02:03:24.360
And I was going to play it last
night so I could talk about it.

02:03:24.360 --> 02:03:27.230
And then my daughters
hid my iPad on me.

02:03:27.230 --> 02:03:29.400
It's very hard to
download a game

02:03:29.400 --> 02:03:32.140
when you don't have the
device to download it onto.

02:03:32.140 --> 02:03:34.440
So has anybody else
played this game?

02:03:34.440 --> 02:03:34.940
OK.

02:03:34.940 --> 02:03:35.689
A few people have.

02:03:38.970 --> 02:03:41.590
Your goal in this game
is you're a virus.

02:03:41.590 --> 02:03:43.610
You would like to evolve
and hopefully take out

02:03:43.610 --> 02:03:45.960
all of humanity.

02:03:45.960 --> 02:03:48.610
And as you're playing the
game as the player guiding

02:03:48.610 --> 02:03:52.960
the virus's development, you
get to make a lot of choices.

02:03:52.960 --> 02:03:54.240
How lethal is it?

02:03:54.240 --> 02:03:56.020
What kind of
symptoms do you have?

02:03:56.020 --> 02:03:58.200
How easy is it to spread?

02:03:58.200 --> 02:04:00.460
My daughters are
working on the infect

02:04:00.460 --> 02:04:04.020
the whole planet with a
completely symptomless disease

02:04:04.020 --> 02:04:06.760
tactic, and then evolve
quickly up to lethality

02:04:06.760 --> 02:04:09.709
and take everybody out.

02:04:09.709 --> 02:04:11.000
They haven't succeeded at this.

02:04:11.000 --> 02:04:12.580
It sounds like the
perfect strategy.

02:04:12.580 --> 02:04:14.038
But they haven't
succeeded at this.

02:04:14.038 --> 02:04:16.790
Because you kind of need
symptoms to cause damage.

02:04:16.790 --> 02:04:18.819
And they can't evolve
the symptoms fast enough.

02:04:18.819 --> 02:04:20.360
Once they've gotten
everyone infected

02:04:20.360 --> 02:04:22.940
and they're going from
completely harmless to deadly,

02:04:22.940 --> 02:04:26.600
they can't manage to
evolve it fast enough.

02:04:26.600 --> 02:04:29.496
So it's got a lot
of interesting play

02:04:29.496 --> 02:04:31.620
there, where you've got a
lot of different tactics.

02:04:31.620 --> 02:04:33.940
I think they can get it
someday, but they haven't yet.

02:04:33.940 --> 02:04:37.350
They'll need to try
a different tactic.

02:04:37.350 --> 02:04:40.710
And finally, a game I have
played an awful lot of

02:04:40.710 --> 02:04:41.680
is Pandemic.

02:04:41.680 --> 02:04:43.840
Who here has played Pandemic?

02:04:43.840 --> 02:04:45.560
OK.

02:04:45.560 --> 02:04:48.960
So what is the main
tactic and resource

02:04:48.960 --> 02:04:51.580
you have in this game,
if you've played it?

02:04:54.350 --> 02:04:55.030
AUDIENCE: Turns.

02:04:55.030 --> 02:04:57.300
SARA VERRILLI:
Turns-- well, time.

02:04:57.300 --> 02:04:57.890
Time.

02:04:57.890 --> 02:04:58.750
Yeah.

02:04:58.750 --> 02:05:00.560
In a lot of ways, in this game,
what you're playing against

02:05:00.560 --> 02:05:01.060
is time.

02:05:01.060 --> 02:05:03.010
Because when you
run out of the deck,

02:05:03.010 --> 02:05:06.930
if you haven't managed to
clear things, the game is over.

02:05:06.930 --> 02:05:09.600
And the resource you've got,
and the choices you've got,

02:05:09.600 --> 02:05:14.014
is where people are going and
which area they're fighting.

02:05:14.014 --> 02:05:15.680
The overall plan of
the game, of course,

02:05:15.680 --> 02:05:19.280
is there are four
epidemics raging.

02:05:19.280 --> 02:05:20.330
You're the CDC.

02:05:20.330 --> 02:05:23.110
You need to find cures
for all the plagues

02:05:23.110 --> 02:05:29.160
before they take out
the rest of humanity.

02:05:29.160 --> 02:05:31.770
And so you have to balance
both your long-term strategy

02:05:31.770 --> 02:05:33.786
of finding a cure
for each of diseases

02:05:33.786 --> 02:05:35.410
with the short-term
strategy of keeping

02:05:35.410 --> 02:05:38.529
the diseases under
control, so that you

02:05:38.529 --> 02:05:41.024
don't end up with
everything being destroyed.

02:05:44.517 --> 02:05:47.012
PHILLIP TAN: All right, my turn.

02:05:47.012 --> 02:05:52.991
[INAUDIBLE] Who's
played Dominion?

02:05:52.991 --> 02:05:54.010
OK, pretty popular.

02:05:54.010 --> 02:05:57.600
I certainly recommend it
as a good introduction

02:05:57.600 --> 02:06:01.170
to the basic idea of
deck-building games.

02:06:01.170 --> 02:06:04.710
Actually, how many people
have played Magic, Yu-Gi-Oh!,

02:06:04.710 --> 02:06:06.150
Pokemon card game?

02:06:06.150 --> 02:06:06.910
OK.

02:06:06.910 --> 02:06:09.270
All right, a lot of that.

02:06:09.270 --> 02:06:12.115
In many of those games, and
in Dominion, a lot of the fun

02:06:12.115 --> 02:06:14.380
is just building
your own machine,

02:06:14.380 --> 02:06:16.490
your own little
engine, that is going

02:06:16.490 --> 02:06:18.000
to execute out your strategy.

02:06:18.000 --> 02:06:20.314
Now your engine happens
to be a deck of cards.

02:06:20.314 --> 02:06:22.730
You get shuffled up, so it's
in some sort of random order.

02:06:22.730 --> 02:06:26.025
But you get to choose
what cards go in there.

02:06:26.025 --> 02:06:28.520
In a collectible card game
like Magic: the Gathering,

02:06:28.520 --> 02:06:31.080
you are buying those cards,
and then assembling the cards,

02:06:31.080 --> 02:06:33.150
or there's a draft
[? mechanic ?].

02:06:33.150 --> 02:06:35.340
In a game like
Dominion, there is

02:06:35.340 --> 02:06:38.330
a way where you buy more cards
while you're playing the game.

02:06:38.330 --> 02:06:41.140
But in the end, what
it all comes down to is

02:06:41.140 --> 02:06:44.310
as you play this game, you get
cards that go into your deck.

02:06:44.310 --> 02:06:46.747
They are going to end up
being shuffled in your deck.

02:06:46.747 --> 02:06:48.330
And at some random
time in the future,

02:06:48.330 --> 02:06:49.640
it's going to get played out.

02:06:49.640 --> 02:06:52.270
And so the cards that you
choose to put into your deck

02:06:52.270 --> 02:06:55.820
turns out to be your main
means of motivating you

02:06:55.820 --> 02:06:58.490
towards a [INAUDIBLE] strategy.

02:06:58.490 --> 02:07:01.540
There are a range of different
ways to play this game,

02:07:01.540 --> 02:07:05.620
and different possible
success criteria.

02:07:08.600 --> 02:07:11.070
And the really interesting
thing about the Dominion deck

02:07:11.070 --> 02:07:15.170
is I think it gets something
like over 20 different kinds

02:07:15.170 --> 02:07:18.270
of cards in a box of Dominion.

02:07:18.270 --> 02:07:23.630
But you only play with 10 of
them-- 10 plus victory points.

02:07:23.630 --> 02:07:27.660
So every time you play
the game, the strategy

02:07:27.660 --> 02:07:29.370
starts by just seeing,
what are the 10

02:07:29.370 --> 02:07:33.880
cards I've got in front of
me for this session of play?

02:07:33.880 --> 02:07:36.270
And then you choose, out
of these 10 cards, what

02:07:36.270 --> 02:07:39.489
are the cards that I'm going to
select and in what proportion,

02:07:39.489 --> 02:07:41.280
in order to build this
engine that is going

02:07:41.280 --> 02:07:43.134
to motivate me towards victory?

02:07:43.134 --> 02:07:44.300
So it's an interesting game.

02:07:44.300 --> 02:07:45.841
I would strongly
recommend it, if you

02:07:45.841 --> 02:07:47.824
know someone who's got
a copy of this game

02:07:47.824 --> 02:07:48.865
or any of the expansions.

02:07:48.865 --> 02:07:50.031
They're all interchangeable.

02:07:55.260 --> 02:08:01.180
Drop7-- mostly played on mobile,
although I think there is also

02:08:01.180 --> 02:08:03.250
a browser version of this game.

02:08:03.250 --> 02:08:04.790
How many of you
have played this?

02:08:04.790 --> 02:08:05.600
Yeah.

02:08:05.600 --> 02:08:09.140
Perfect for a T ride, I find.

02:08:09.140 --> 02:08:12.970
You can finish a session
in a single trip on the T.

02:08:12.970 --> 02:08:15.950
The idea is that you're
just dropping one number

02:08:15.950 --> 02:08:17.770
from the top of the screen.

02:08:17.770 --> 02:08:21.440
And that number ranges
anywhere between one to seven.

02:08:21.440 --> 02:08:25.320
And if you manage to
make a row of numbers

02:08:25.320 --> 02:08:31.880
that add up to-- let's
say I have a row of sixes.

02:08:31.880 --> 02:08:33.800
And I have six sixes in a row.

02:08:33.800 --> 02:08:35.950
Then all of the sixes
are going to disappear.

02:08:35.950 --> 02:08:37.580
And it's going to
also clear out some

02:08:37.580 --> 02:08:40.100
of those gray circles where
you don't know the numbers yet.

02:08:40.100 --> 02:08:42.680
It's going to review the
numbers behind these gray tiles.

02:08:42.680 --> 02:08:45.450
You can think of them as tiles
that were turned upside down.

02:08:45.450 --> 02:08:48.390
So what you really, really
want to make is chains.

02:08:48.390 --> 02:08:53.440
Chains are where, if I have a
six, five, four, three, two,

02:08:53.440 --> 02:08:56.295
one, then what happens is
that six is going to burst.

02:08:56.295 --> 02:08:57.670
Then that five is
going to burst.

02:08:57.670 --> 02:08:58.370
Then that four is
going to burst.

02:08:58.370 --> 02:09:00.110
Then a three, and
so on and so forth.

02:09:00.110 --> 02:09:01.870
You set up these massive chains.

02:09:01.870 --> 02:09:03.539
And basically,
you're just assigning

02:09:03.539 --> 02:09:04.830
how you're going to place this.

02:09:04.830 --> 02:09:09.270
And if you played a
game like Puyo Puyo--

02:09:09.270 --> 02:09:11.700
I'm trying to think-- certain
kinds of Match 3 games

02:09:11.700 --> 02:09:17.420
like Bejeweled, you'll get this
sort of chain reaction feeling.

02:09:17.420 --> 02:09:19.750
And some games more
than others encourage

02:09:19.750 --> 02:09:25.070
you to set up these chains
before you drop the triggering

02:09:25.070 --> 02:09:25.830
piece.

02:09:25.830 --> 02:09:28.140
Drop7 is very much about that.

02:09:28.140 --> 02:09:33.290
So I believe, if you can
find it on a browser,

02:09:33.290 --> 02:09:34.140
it should be free.

02:09:34.140 --> 02:09:37.000
I'm not so sure whether
the iOS versions are free.

02:09:37.000 --> 02:09:37.700
They are?

02:09:37.700 --> 02:09:38.200
Great.

02:09:40.910 --> 02:09:43.880
I keep forgetting the
computer is on this side.

02:09:43.880 --> 02:09:47.650
The StarCraft II visual novel.

02:09:47.650 --> 02:09:49.077
AUDIENCE: Wait, is it done?

02:09:49.077 --> 02:09:49.910
PHILLIP TAN: No, no.

02:09:49.910 --> 02:09:52.720
It's still in development.

02:09:52.720 --> 02:09:54.750
Full disclosure, I am
a Kickstarter backer

02:09:54.750 --> 02:09:56.550
of this game.

02:09:56.550 --> 02:09:58.870
As has been mentioned
many, many times,

02:09:58.870 --> 02:10:01.430
I am a StarCraft II player.

02:10:01.430 --> 02:10:04.400
But I am not encouraging
you to go and learn

02:10:04.400 --> 02:10:05.350
that over the weekend.

02:10:05.350 --> 02:10:08.970
Because StarCraft II is more
of a lifestyle kind of thing.

02:10:08.970 --> 02:10:11.184
[LAUGHTER]

02:10:11.184 --> 02:10:12.600
But if you're just
kind of wanting

02:10:12.600 --> 02:10:15.590
to see what the
strategy is about,

02:10:15.590 --> 02:10:18.789
this is an interesting
game where--

02:10:18.789 --> 02:10:20.330
if you've ever played
a visual novel,

02:10:20.330 --> 02:10:24.150
they're kind of like Choose Your
Own Adventure in digital form.

02:10:24.150 --> 02:10:26.080
And they are usually
very strong narrative-

02:10:26.080 --> 02:10:27.560
and character-driven games.

02:10:27.560 --> 02:10:33.330
You play a teenager who has
moved to Korea in the hopes

02:10:33.330 --> 02:10:35.950
to start his or her
pro gaming career.

02:10:35.950 --> 02:10:39.920
And you go into a LAN center.

02:10:39.920 --> 02:10:42.760
And you play random
games against people.

02:10:42.760 --> 02:10:45.010
Only these are the kinds of
decisions you get to make.

02:10:45.010 --> 02:10:46.920
Which strategy are
you going to go for?

02:10:46.920 --> 02:10:50.890
I usually find this to be
a really, really good way

02:10:50.890 --> 02:10:54.740
of conveying the macro-level
decisions, the really, really

02:10:54.740 --> 02:10:56.517
high-level long-term
strategic decisions

02:10:56.517 --> 02:10:57.600
that you're going to make.

02:10:57.600 --> 02:11:00.040
Because you're not
actually playing StarCraft.

02:11:00.040 --> 02:11:05.020
You are choosing between
two or three choices.

02:11:05.020 --> 02:11:06.700
And then it plays out.

02:11:06.700 --> 02:11:10.380
But it gives you a good idea of
the kind of high-level decision

02:11:10.380 --> 02:11:10.880
making.

02:11:10.880 --> 02:11:13.569
Whereas most people see
someone play StarCraft as like,

02:11:13.569 --> 02:11:14.610
the [KEY-CLACKING NOISE].

