Cool.

02:11:47.520 --> 02:11:50.040
So this one I really
like as an example.

02:11:50.040 --> 02:11:51.800
Eww, it looks awful
on the screen, though.

02:11:51.800 --> 02:11:53.425
So I really like this
one as an example

02:11:53.425 --> 02:11:57.170
because it has not
yet been published.

02:11:57.170 --> 02:11:59.800
On their website they
have their alpha build.

02:11:59.800 --> 02:12:04.120
And if you were to buy their
game, what you would see

02:12:04.120 --> 02:12:05.080
is the beta build.

02:12:05.080 --> 02:12:07.880
And then later on, when it
actually does publish-- you

02:12:07.880 --> 02:12:09.400
guys can even see
this on YouTube.

02:12:09.400 --> 02:12:11.816
You can see what it's going
to look like when you actually

02:12:11.816 --> 02:12:13.460
buy the final game.

02:12:13.460 --> 02:12:15.370
It plays exactly the same.

02:12:15.370 --> 02:12:18.230
It looks polished.

02:12:18.230 --> 02:12:20.344
It's a really good
example of here's

02:12:20.344 --> 02:12:22.260
a game that works and
is functionally perfect.

02:12:22.260 --> 02:12:23.760
And they could have
just shipped it.

02:12:23.760 --> 02:12:26.290
And I'm really glad that
did, because I play it a lot.

02:12:26.290 --> 02:12:27.835
And when they
finally ship it, it's

02:12:27.835 --> 02:12:29.460
still going to play
the exact same way.

02:12:29.460 --> 02:12:30.430
It's just going to be
a little bit prettier.

02:12:30.430 --> 02:12:31.070
And it really doesn't matter.

02:12:31.070 --> 02:12:32.130
I don't really care about that.

02:12:32.130 --> 02:12:34.620
That's something that we're
going to stress in this game.

02:12:34.620 --> 02:12:37.220
We're more concerned about
that, is it playable?

02:12:37.220 --> 02:12:37.900
Does it work?

02:12:37.900 --> 02:12:40.510
Can I understand how to play
it-- more so than the pretty,

02:12:40.510 --> 02:12:44.490
more so than the aesthetic
and visual polish.

02:12:44.490 --> 02:12:49.004
So in this game, it is a
game about managing a subway.

02:12:49.004 --> 02:12:50.420
All of the sudden
a subway station

02:12:50.420 --> 02:12:51.560
appears in the middle of space.

02:12:51.560 --> 02:12:53.018
And you have to
build a line to it.

02:12:53.018 --> 02:12:54.510
So you build your line.

02:12:54.510 --> 02:12:57.080
And then passengers randomly
appear on the subway trains.

02:12:57.080 --> 02:12:59.580
But you don't have to actually
get them from place to place.

02:12:59.580 --> 02:13:00.970
You don't control the trains.

02:13:00.970 --> 02:13:02.470
You just build the lines.

02:13:02.470 --> 02:13:04.170
The trains move on their own.

02:13:04.170 --> 02:13:06.290
And they're moving
at a constant rate.

02:13:06.290 --> 02:13:07.970
So you can kind of
guess when the train

02:13:07.970 --> 02:13:10.030
is going to get to the station.

02:13:10.030 --> 02:13:13.840
There are strategies
to-- you can move

02:13:13.840 --> 02:13:15.534
your lines around a little bit.

02:13:15.534 --> 02:13:17.700
But once your lines are in
place, for the most part,

02:13:17.700 --> 02:13:18.324
they're static.

02:13:18.324 --> 02:13:20.200
You can't really change
them all that much.

02:13:20.200 --> 02:13:21.740
So there's some
limitations going on

02:13:21.740 --> 02:13:24.930
between how much you
can move a line or not.

02:13:24.930 --> 02:13:26.580
At the end, if you
last a week, it's

02:13:26.580 --> 02:13:28.163
going to give you
one of three options

02:13:28.163 --> 02:13:29.810
to do a power-up, basically.

02:13:29.810 --> 02:13:33.410
Either you can build a
new line, add a new train,

02:13:33.410 --> 02:13:34.900
increase the
capacity of a train.

02:13:34.900 --> 02:13:36.650
So you're making a
permanent choice there.

02:13:36.650 --> 02:13:38.400
And that's going to
affect the later game.

02:13:38.400 --> 02:13:40.730
So you're making all
sorts of these decisions

02:13:40.730 --> 02:13:42.169
at both a macro and micro level.

02:13:42.169 --> 02:13:44.210
And there's a really good
write-up about the game

02:13:44.210 --> 02:13:47.570
right there, if you
just want to read that.

02:13:47.570 --> 02:13:51.150
FTL-- I lost a ton
of productivity

02:13:51.150 --> 02:13:53.630
a few months ago
because of this game.

02:13:53.630 --> 02:13:56.931
It is a game about
fighting in spaceships

02:13:56.931 --> 02:13:59.180
without actually controlling
all the fighting so much.

02:13:59.180 --> 02:14:04.470
You're actually upgrading your
ship, increasing your capacity,

02:14:04.470 --> 02:14:07.730
buying crew members-- and
hoping your crew members survive

02:14:07.730 --> 02:14:09.170
is a lot of it.

02:14:09.170 --> 02:14:13.619
You could-- and I
do this-- manually

02:14:13.619 --> 02:14:14.660
control all your weapons.

02:14:14.660 --> 02:14:17.034
And actually to succeed,
you really do have to.

02:14:17.034 --> 02:14:19.200
Because the interesting
thing with this game is it's

02:14:19.200 --> 02:14:20.390
a perma-death game.

02:14:20.390 --> 02:14:22.602
As soon as you die, it's dead.

02:14:22.602 --> 02:14:23.560
You have to start over.

02:14:23.560 --> 02:14:24.768
You have to restart the game.

02:14:24.768 --> 02:14:28.150
Luckily the game only takes
about three hours to play.

02:14:28.150 --> 02:14:30.880
But you're lucky if you get
through those three hours.

02:14:30.880 --> 02:14:32.870
And when you finally
get to the last boss,

02:14:32.870 --> 02:14:36.987
and you're there-- the thing
about this game is in order

02:14:36.987 --> 02:14:39.570
to get to that boss, there's all
sorts of different challenges

02:14:39.570 --> 02:14:40.630
you're facing.

02:14:40.630 --> 02:14:42.370
And you're making
these decisions about,

02:14:42.370 --> 02:14:44.000
do I buy this weapon
or that weapon

02:14:44.000 --> 02:14:45.740
to help me with the thing
I know that I'm going

02:14:45.740 --> 02:14:46.864
to face in the next sector?

02:14:46.864 --> 02:14:48.420
Because I'm losing health.

02:14:48.420 --> 02:14:50.530
I'm really dying here.

02:14:50.530 --> 02:14:52.280
But is this weapon
really going to help me

02:14:52.280 --> 02:14:54.720
when I get to the boss?

02:14:54.720 --> 02:14:56.470
You're constantly
going back and forth.

02:14:56.470 --> 02:14:59.800
So I'll often find, after three
or four, that I'm at the boss

02:14:59.800 --> 02:15:02.330
and I'm completely ill-equipped
to fight this thing.

02:15:02.330 --> 02:15:03.570
And I just die.

02:15:03.570 --> 02:15:05.900
But I do play out to the
end, because it's fun.

02:15:05.900 --> 02:15:08.200
Last game I have--
this one's free online.

02:15:08.200 --> 02:15:09.570
It's called Gridland.

02:15:09.570 --> 02:15:14.440
If anybody's played the game, A
Dark Room, a text-based supply

02:15:14.440 --> 02:15:16.780
chain game, this is
the Match 3 version

02:15:16.780 --> 02:15:19.100
of that game, a little bit.

02:15:19.100 --> 02:15:21.590
There's two stages in
the game-- day and night.

02:15:21.590 --> 02:15:24.070
It's Match 3, so you
just collect three gems.

02:15:24.070 --> 02:15:27.580
And you get whatever the
gems represent-- resources

02:15:27.580 --> 02:15:34.760
like clay, wood, and
stone, food, paper, gems.

02:15:34.760 --> 02:15:38.190
You can upgrade your little
factories to make better gems.

02:15:38.190 --> 02:15:39.699
Every time you
upgrade one of these,

02:15:39.699 --> 02:15:41.240
though-- so if you
upgrade your wood,

02:15:41.240 --> 02:15:42.450
you'll get a better sword.

02:15:42.450 --> 02:15:44.045
If you upgrade your
clay, which you

02:15:44.045 --> 02:15:47.170
need to make the
better wood, you're

02:15:47.170 --> 02:15:49.740
going to get in the
nighttime a stronger monster.

02:15:49.740 --> 02:15:52.870
So in this case, this
is immediately daytime

02:15:52.870 --> 02:15:54.410
and then shifted over to night.

02:15:54.410 --> 02:15:55.930
The exact same layout is there.

02:15:55.930 --> 02:16:00.371
It's just the logs
have become shields.

02:16:00.371 --> 02:16:03.590
The little blue things that
are supposed to be iron

02:16:03.590 --> 02:16:04.720
become swords.

02:16:04.720 --> 02:16:08.550
And all the other
things become enemies.

02:16:08.550 --> 02:16:11.900
So a lot of the
strategy for this game

02:16:11.900 --> 02:16:14.330
is, what's going to help me now?

02:16:14.330 --> 02:16:16.257
What's going to help
me in the future?

02:16:16.257 --> 02:16:17.840
What's going to hurt
me in the future?

02:16:17.840 --> 02:16:19.465
And what's going to
hurt me immediately

02:16:19.465 --> 02:16:21.670
as I switch over to night?

02:16:21.670 --> 02:16:24.012
Once I get into the
night mode, I'll

02:16:24.012 --> 02:16:25.970
have known exactly what
I'm going to be facing.

02:16:25.970 --> 02:16:27.937
Because I set that stage up.

02:16:27.937 --> 02:16:30.520
So unlike Bejeweled where you're
just constantly just clicking

02:16:30.520 --> 02:16:32.040
things, or Candy Crush
where you're just

02:16:32.040 --> 02:16:33.139
constantly just
clicking things, there's

02:16:33.139 --> 02:16:34.430
actually no time limit on this.

02:16:34.430 --> 02:16:35.950
And it took me--
it's embarrassing

02:16:35.950 --> 02:16:38.282
how long it took me-- a day
or two to realize that I

02:16:38.282 --> 02:16:39.490
didn't have to play that way.

02:16:39.490 --> 02:16:42.495
I could just wait,
pause, and play.

02:16:42.495 --> 02:16:44.370
There wasn't going to
be a time limit pushing

02:16:44.370 --> 02:16:48.126
me to continue moving forward.

02:16:48.126 --> 02:16:50.000
And that's an interesting
presentation thing.

02:16:50.000 --> 02:16:51.466
When you're
presenting your games,

02:16:51.466 --> 02:16:53.299
especially if you're
using a previous genre,

02:16:53.299 --> 02:16:55.548
there's going to be genre
conventions that the players

02:16:55.548 --> 02:16:56.639
are going to understand.

02:16:56.639 --> 02:16:59.120
That is going to shape
their user experience.

02:16:59.120 --> 02:17:03.840
And we'll be talking about
that about project three.

